232
00:14:01,424 --> 00:14:03,586
what can I bring you
from the market?

233
00:14:03,885 --> 00:14:06,377
A rose.
Like the one in the painting.

234
00:14:06,512 --> 00:14:08,378
You ask for that every year!

235
00:14:08,556 --> 00:14:10,217
And every year you bring it.

236
00:14:10,308 --> 00:14:11,548
Then I shall
bring you another.

237
00:14:12,393 --> 00:14:14,179
You have my word.

238
00:14:15,271 --> 00:14:17,854
- Goodbye, Papa.
- Goodbye, Belle.

239
00:14:18,399 --> 00:14:20,231
- Come on, Philippe.
- (PHILIPPE WHINNIES)

240
00:14:20,610 --> 00:14:21,610
You know the way.

241
00:14:21,778 --> 00:14:22,893
I'll see you tomorrow!

242
00:14:23,029 --> 00:14:26,397
Right.
Tomorrow, with the rose.

243
00:14:26,491 --> 00:14:27,491
(CHUCKLES)

244
00:14:32,580 --> 00:14:34,366
Stay safe.

245
00:14:59,190 --> 00:15:01,522
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

246
00:15:13,621 --> 00:15:15,237
GIRL: What are you doing?

247
00:15:16,290 --> 00:15:17,290
The laundry.

248
00:15:18,793 --> 00:15:21,376
Come! Come!

249
00:15:21,712 --> 00:15:23,623
(CHURCH BELL TOLLING)

250
00:15:26,509 --> 00:15:28,295
"The blue bird..."

251
00:15:29,303 --> 00:15:31,670
"That flies..."

252
00:15:32,640 --> 00:15:35,098
"over the dark..."

253
00:15:35,184 --> 00:15:36,515
"wood."

254
00:15:36,644 --> 00:15:37,805
That was amazing!

255
00:15:38,980 --> 00:15:41,142
What on earth are you doing?

256
00:15:41,315 --> 00:15:43,682
Teaching another girl to read?

257
00:15:43,818 --> 00:15:45,809
Isn't one enough?

258
00:15:45,987 --> 00:15:47,648
We have to do something.

259
00:15:50,283 --> 00:15:51,739
(MEN GRUNTING)

260
00:15:59,667 --> 00:16:01,704
You are the wildest...

261
00:16:01,836 --> 00:16:04,624
most gorgeous thing
I have ever seen.

262
00:16:05,214 --> 00:16:06,500
Nobody deserves you.

263
00:16:06,674 --> 00:16:09,336
But at least I know
our children will be beautiful.

264
00:16:09,510 --> 00:16:11,797
Am I catching you
at a bad time?

265
00:16:11,888 --> 00:16:14,630
- What is it, LeFou?
- A certain damsel is in distress.

266
00:16:16,893 --> 00:16:19,931
Ah. It's hero time.

267
00:16:20,730 --> 00:16:22,596
I'm not done with you yet.

268
00:16:25,276 --> 00:16:26,311
Me, neither.

269
00:16:27,695 --> 00:16:29,840
GASTON: Belle! I heard you had trouble
with the Headmaster.

270
00:16:29,864 --> 00:16:31,354
He never liked me either.

271
00:16:32,200 --> 00:16:35,488
Can I give you a little advice
about the villagers though?

272
00:16:35,578 --> 00:16:38,696
They're never going to trust
the kind of change you're trying to bring.

273
00:16:39,790 --> 00:16:42,373
All I wanted was to teach
a child to read.

274
00:16:42,627 --> 00:16:44,959
The only children you should
concern yourself with...

275
00:16:45,796 --> 00:16:46,831
are your own.

276
00:16:48,216 --> 00:16:49,377
I'm...

277
00:16:49,509 --> 00:16:51,466
not ready to have children.

278
00:16:51,552 --> 00:16:53,213
Maybe you haven't
met the right man.

279
00:16:53,387 --> 00:16:56,470
It's a small village, Gaston.
I've met them all.

280
00:16:57,475 --> 00:16:59,933
Well, maybe
you should take another look.

281
00:17:00,102 --> 00:17:01,809
Some of us have changed.

282
00:17:02,104 --> 00:17:02,889
Gaston...

283
00:17:03,064 --> 00:17:05,101
we could never
make each other happy.

284
00:17:05,566 --> 00:17:08,354
No one can change that much.

285
00:17:08,444 --> 00:17:09,559
Oh, Belle.

286
00:17:10,905 --> 00:17:12,985
Do you know what happens
to spinsters in this village

287
00:17:13,074 --> 00:17:14,235
after their fathers die?

288
00:17:14,408 --> 00:17:16,240
AGATHE: Coins? Got any spare coins?

289
00:17:16,410 --> 00:17:19,402
They beg for scraps,
like poor Agathe.

290
00:17:19,497 --> 00:17:22,080
This is our world, Belle.

291
00:17:22,792 --> 00:17:25,329
For simple folk like us,
it doesn't get any better.

292
00:17:25,419 --> 00:17:27,160
I might be a farm girl.

293
00:17:27,338 --> 00:17:29,750
But, I'm not simple...

294
00:17:29,924 --> 00:17:33,838
and I'm never going to
marry you, Gaston.

295
00:17:33,928 --> 00:17:34,963
I'm sorry!

296
00:17:46,774 --> 00:17:47,774
(EXHALES)

297
00:17:51,279 --> 00:17:52,940
Can you imagine?

298
00:17:53,030 --> 00:17:55,988
Me? The wife
of that boorish...

299
00:17:56,117 --> 00:17:57,117
brainless...

300
00:17:57,785 --> 00:18:01,494
♪ (SINGING) <i>Madame Gaston, ♪
♪ can't you just see it</i> ♪

301
00:18:01,664 --> 00:18:04,247
♪ <i>Madame Gaston, ♪
♪ his little wife</i> ♪

302
00:18:04,333 --> 00:18:05,368
♪ <i>Ugh!</i> ♪

303
00:18:05,459 --> 00:18:08,668
♪ <i>No, sir, not me, ♪
♪ I guarantee it</i> ♪

304
00:18:08,838 --> 00:18:12,832
♪ <i>I want much more ♪
♪ than this provincial life</i> ♪

305
00:18:23,060 --> 00:18:28,146
♪ <i>I want adventure ♪
♪ in the great wide somewhere</i> ♪

306
00:18:28,983 --> 00:18:32,977
♪ <i>I want it more than I can tell</i> ♪

307
00:18:34,155 --> 00:18:38,069
♪ <i>And for once it might be grand</i> ♪

308
00:18:39,035 --> 00:18:43,074
♪ <i>To have someone understand</i> ♪

309
00:18:44,206 --> 00:18:50,202
♪ <i>I want so much more ♪
♪ Than they've got planned</i> ♪

310
00:18:53,549 --> 00:18:54,880
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

311
00:18:58,804 --> 00:18:59,839
(PHILIPPE NEIGHS)

312
00:19:04,435 --> 00:19:05,345
The woods are lovely.

313
00:19:05,436 --> 00:19:08,349
I only wish I recognized them.

314
00:19:08,481 --> 00:19:11,724
Do you know where we are,
Philippe? Because I don't.

315
00:19:13,194 --> 00:19:14,650
(WHINNYING)

316
00:19:16,864 --> 00:19:19,697
It's all right.
It's all right, Philippe.

317
00:19:22,036 --> 00:19:23,526
Hmm.

318
00:19:24,080 --> 00:19:26,321
Yes, we can go this way.
(CLICKS TONGUE)

319
00:19:26,415 --> 00:19:28,156
Go on. To the right.

320
00:19:28,876 --> 00:19:30,958
That's it. Steady!

321
00:19:31,128 --> 00:19:32,539
Walk on!

322
00:19:32,963 --> 00:19:34,169
One path closes...

323
00:19:34,256 --> 00:19:35,542
another one opens.

324
00:19:37,259 --> 00:19:39,751
It's all right, boy.
It's just a bit of snow.

325
00:19:39,887 --> 00:19:41,423
In June.

326
00:19:42,723 --> 00:19:43,723
Mind your step.

327
00:19:44,392 --> 00:19:45,882
It's slippery.

328
00:19:51,982 --> 00:19:53,268
(NEIGHS)

329
00:19:55,361 --> 00:19:56,396
(GROWLING)

330
00:19:56,654 --> 00:19:59,112
Go! Go, Philippe!
Come on! Come on!

331
00:19:59,281 --> 00:20:01,318
- (HOWLING)
- Whoa.

332
00:20:02,076 --> 00:20:03,316
(WOLVES GROWLING)

333
00:20:07,206 --> 00:20:08,617
Come on!

334
00:20:09,417 --> 00:20:11,124
Go! Philippe, go! Go, go!

335
00:20:16,966 --> 00:20:18,377
Whoa!

336
00:20:20,302 --> 00:20:21,963
(MAURICE YELLS AND GRUNTS)

337
00:20:22,054 --> 00:20:24,091
(PHILIPPE WHINNYING)

338
00:20:28,477 --> 00:20:30,059
(GRUNTING)

339
00:20:34,984 --> 00:20:36,645
(GROWLING)

340
00:20:40,573 --> 00:20:41,938
(EXCLAIMING)

341
00:20:43,784 --> 00:20:45,240
Philippe!

342
00:20:46,704 --> 00:20:48,069
Good boy.

343
00:20:50,374 --> 00:20:52,285
Go, boy. Go!

344
00:21:03,262 --> 00:21:04,844
(WOLF HOWLING)

345
00:21:05,431 --> 00:21:07,547
Oh, Philippe,
you saved my life.

346
00:21:08,559 --> 00:21:10,266
Well done. Yes.

347
00:21:11,812 --> 00:21:14,349
They'll have to get
their dinner somewhere else,

348
00:21:14,482 --> 00:21:15,688
won't they? (CHUCKLES)

349
00:21:15,775 --> 00:21:17,812
(PANTING)

350
00:21:20,821 --> 00:21:21,821
(GRUNTS)

351
00:21:23,032 --> 00:21:24,272
Look!

352
00:21:24,450 --> 00:21:25,611
There's hay.

353
00:21:26,285 --> 00:21:27,320
And water.

354
00:21:27,495 --> 00:21:29,987
You're all set, my old friend.

355
00:21:30,998 --> 00:21:35,287
I'll go pay my respects
to our unwitting host.

356
00:21:36,003 --> 00:21:38,165
Whoever that may be.

357
00:22:06,158 --> 00:22:07,158
Hmm.

358
00:22:12,706 --> 00:22:13,992
Thank you.

359
00:22:14,792 --> 00:22:15,998
Thank...

360
00:22:22,716 --> 00:22:23,877
Hello?

361
00:22:26,470 --> 00:22:27,881
Hello?

362
00:22:27,972 --> 00:22:29,633
Sorry to intrude.

363
00:22:29,723 --> 00:22:31,839
I'm just a traveler...

364
00:22:32,434 --> 00:22:34,926
seeking shelter
from the storm.

365
00:22:36,564 --> 00:22:38,396
Sorry to disturb you.

366
00:22:43,946 --> 00:22:45,482
Anyone home?

367
00:22:45,573 --> 00:22:46,938
Anyone awake?

368
00:22:49,869 --> 00:22:51,576
He must have
lost his way in the woods.

369
00:22:51,704 --> 00:22:53,615
Shut up, you idiot!

370
00:22:55,291 --> 00:22:56,907
Excuse me?

371
00:22:58,127 --> 00:22:59,788
Hmm.

372
00:23:00,921 --> 00:23:02,707
Beautiful.

373
00:23:08,262 --> 00:23:09,923
Extraordinary.

374
00:23:10,097 --> 00:23:12,179
(MUSIC PLAYING)

375
00:23:19,565 --> 00:23:20,726
A man of taste.

376
00:23:20,816 --> 00:23:22,432
He was talking about me.

377
00:23:25,112 --> 00:23:26,147
Oops!

378
00:23:29,199 --> 00:23:30,199
(MAURICE STUTTERS)

379
00:23:38,292 --> 00:23:41,284
Well, wherever you are...

380
00:23:42,254 --> 00:23:45,918
I'm just going to warm myself
by the fire.

381
00:23:50,596 --> 00:23:51,596
(COUGHS)

382
00:23:53,390 --> 00:23:54,721
That's better.

383
00:23:55,851 --> 00:23:57,512
Oh, much better.

384
00:24:01,649 --> 00:24:02,649
(DISTANT CLATTERING)

385
00:24:13,786 --> 00:24:14,786
Ooh.

386
00:24:15,871 --> 00:24:17,361
Thank you.

387
00:24:31,011 --> 00:24:34,094
Mum said I wasn't supposed to move
because it might be scary.

388
00:24:35,849 --> 00:24:37,010
Sorry.

389
00:24:41,480 --> 00:24:43,062
It's all right.

390
00:24:48,362 --> 00:24:49,362
I, uh...

391
00:24:50,197 --> 00:24:51,197
I cannot...

392
00:24:51,699 --> 00:24:55,363
thank you enough
for your hospitality.

393
00:24:56,036 --> 00:24:57,401
I'll...

394
00:24:59,081 --> 00:25:02,039
bid you adieu...

395
00:25:02,209 --> 00:25:03,620
(THUNDER CRACKING)

396
00:25:03,711 --> 00:25:05,748
and good night.

397
00:25:06,088 --> 00:25:08,500
Come on, Philippe! Go! Go!

398
00:25:11,343 --> 00:25:13,209
No, wait, wait, wait!

399
00:25:13,345 --> 00:25:15,177
Roses. I nearly forgot.

400
00:25:16,015 --> 00:25:17,722
We're safe here.

401
00:25:18,600 --> 00:25:20,511
I promised Belle a rose.

402
00:25:36,493 --> 00:25:37,493
(EXCLAIMS)

403
00:25:40,414 --> 00:25:42,030
(GROWLING)

404
00:25:42,207 --> 00:25:43,993
(GRUNTING AND HUFFING)

405
00:25:44,752 --> 00:25:45,752
There!

406
00:25:47,421 --> 00:25:49,378
- (THE BEAST ROARING)
- (WHIMPERING)

407
00:25:54,720 --> 00:25:55,720
(WHINNYING)

408
00:26:13,614 --> 00:26:14,614
(PHILIPPE WHINNYING)

409
00:26:23,040 --> 00:26:24,040
Philippe!

410
00:26:30,130 --> 00:26:31,291
What happened?

411
00:26:32,591 --> 00:26:34,047
Where's Papa?

412
00:26:34,468 --> 00:26:35,468
Take me to him!

413
00:26:45,312 --> 00:26:46,723
(WIND BLOWING)

414
00:26:51,819 --> 00:26:52,980
(PHILIPPE WHINNIES)

415
00:27:28,147 --> 00:27:29,979
LUMIÈRE: Look, Cogsworth.

416
00:27:30,190 --> 00:27:31,521
A beautiful girl!

417
00:27:31,692 --> 00:27:34,024
COGSWORTH:
Yes! I can see it's a girl.

418
00:27:34,570 --> 00:27:36,186
I lost my hands, not my eyes.

419
00:27:36,280 --> 00:27:37,816
But what if she is the one?

420
00:27:37,948 --> 00:27:39,655
The one
who'll break the spell?

421
00:27:40,534 --> 00:27:41,615
Who said that?

422
00:27:42,953 --> 00:27:43,953
Who's there?

423
00:27:58,802 --> 00:28:00,008
(MAURICE COUGHS DISTANTLY)

424
00:28:08,937 --> 00:28:10,052
Uh-oh.

425
00:28:12,900 --> 00:28:14,982
(MAURICE CONTINUES COUGHING)

426
00:28:18,739 --> 00:28:19,979
Papa?

427
00:28:27,122 --> 00:28:28,612
Papa, is that you?

428
00:28:28,749 --> 00:28:29,864
Belle!

429
00:28:30,042 --> 00:28:31,578
How did you find me?

430
00:28:31,877 --> 00:28:33,584
Your hands are ice.

431
00:28:33,712 --> 00:28:34,918
We need to get you home.

432
00:28:35,047 --> 00:28:37,084
Belle, you must leave here
at once!

433
00:28:37,216 --> 00:28:39,799
This castle is alive!

434
00:28:39,927 --> 00:28:41,509
Now go, before he finds you!

435
00:28:41,595 --> 00:28:42,676
Who?

436
00:28:42,763 --> 00:28:44,754
(THE BEAST GROWLING)

437
00:28:51,730 --> 00:28:53,437
Who's there?

438
00:28:54,191 --> 00:28:55,602
Who are you?

439
00:28:55,776 --> 00:28:57,562
THE BEAST: Who are you?

440
00:28:57,694 --> 00:28:59,810
I've come for my father.

441
00:29:00,447 --> 00:29:03,439
Your father is a thief.

442
00:29:03,617 --> 00:29:05,028
Liar!

443
00:29:05,118 --> 00:29:06,358
He stole a rose.

444
00:29:06,495 --> 00:29:08,156
I asked for the rose.

445
00:29:08,288 --> 00:29:09,744
Punish me, not him.

446
00:29:09,873 --> 00:29:11,864
No!
He means forever.

447
00:29:13,460 --> 00:29:15,104
Apparently, that's what
happens around here

448
00:29:15,128 --> 00:29:17,335
when you pick a flower.

449
00:29:18,966 --> 00:29:21,173
A life sentence for a rose?

450
00:29:21,301 --> 00:29:23,133
(ROARING)

451
00:29:23,720 --> 00:29:26,337
I received
eternal damnation for one.

452
00:29:26,473 --> 00:29:28,760
I'm merely locking him away.

453
00:29:29,309 --> 00:29:32,518
Now, do you still wish
to take your father's place?

454
00:29:33,647 --> 00:29:34,978
Come into the light.

455
00:29:40,570 --> 00:29:41,731
(GASPS)

456
00:29:43,782 --> 00:29:44,943
Choose.

457
00:29:45,075 --> 00:29:47,407
Belle, I won't
let you do this.

458
00:29:47,494 --> 00:29:49,076
I lost your mother.

459
00:29:49,162 --> 00:29:51,494
I won't lose you, too.

460
00:29:51,623 --> 00:29:53,079
Now, go.

461
00:29:53,166 --> 00:29:54,873
Go! (COUGHS)

462
00:29:56,128 --> 00:29:58,290
All right, Papa. I'll leave.

463
00:30:01,508 --> 00:30:03,090
I need a minute alone with him.

464
00:30:03,176 --> 00:30:04,792
(GRUNTS)

465
00:30:04,886 --> 00:30:05,926
Are you so cold-hearted...

466
00:30:06,096 --> 00:30:08,838
you won't allow a daughter
to kiss her father goodbye?

467
00:30:11,101 --> 00:30:13,342
Forever can spare a minute.

468
00:30:31,955 --> 00:30:36,574
When this door closes,
it will not open again.

469
00:30:41,214 --> 00:30:42,750
I should have been with you.

470
00:30:42,883 --> 00:30:44,965
Oh, no, no.
Belle, listen to me.

471
00:30:45,302 --> 00:30:46,963
It's all right.

472
00:30:47,137 --> 00:30:48,548
Now go.

473
00:30:49,014 --> 00:30:50,379
Live your life.

474
00:30:50,557 --> 00:30:51,888
And forget me.

475
00:30:52,059 --> 00:30:53,424
Forget you?

476
00:30:53,560 --> 00:30:55,426
Everything I am
is because of you.

477
00:30:56,563 --> 00:30:58,145
I love you, Belle.

478
00:30:58,315 --> 00:30:59,555
Don't be afraid.

479
00:31:00,359 --> 00:31:02,191
I love you too, Papa.

480
00:31:02,903 --> 00:31:04,564
I'm not afraid.

481
00:31:07,240 --> 00:31:08,947
And I will escape. I promise.

482
00:31:10,327 --> 00:31:11,408
What?

483
00:31:17,584 --> 00:31:18,870
You took his place.

484
00:31:18,960 --> 00:31:20,542
He's my father.

485
00:31:20,629 --> 00:31:22,119
He's a fool.

486
00:31:22,589 --> 00:31:24,375
And so are you.

487
00:31:25,717 --> 00:31:26,717
Belle...

488
00:31:27,928 --> 00:31:29,043
Papa!

489
00:31:29,137 --> 00:31:30,923
- (GROANING)
- Don't hurt him!

490
00:31:31,014 --> 00:31:32,220
- Papa!
- MAURICE: No!

491
00:31:34,434 --> 00:31:35,595
I'll come back!

492
00:31:36,353 --> 00:31:37,593
I promise!

493
00:31:47,239 --> 00:31:48,239
(GRUNTS)

494
00:31:48,615 --> 00:31:49,615
(GASPS)

495
00:31:49,825 --> 00:31:51,987
LUMIÈRE: Forgive my intrusion,
<i>mademoiselle...</i>

496
00:31:52,160 --> 00:31:55,152
but I have come to escort you
to your room.

497
00:31:55,414 --> 00:31:56,996
My room?

498
00:31:57,874 --> 00:31:59,310
- But I thought...
- LUMIÈRE: Oh, what?

499
00:31:59,334 --> 00:32:03,077
That "Once this door closes
it will not open again"?

500
00:32:03,171 --> 00:32:05,128
(IMITATES ROAR) I know.

501
00:32:05,257 --> 00:32:06,292
He gets so dramatic.

502
00:32:06,383 --> 00:32:08,124
- Hello.
- (GASPS)

503
00:32:08,635 --> 00:32:09,635
(GRUNTS)

504
00:32:09,719 --> 00:32:10,719
- Ooh!
- (SHRIEKS)

505
00:32:12,472 --> 00:32:13,883
Oh, you are very strong.

506
00:32:14,057 --> 00:32:15,673
This is a great quality.

507
00:32:16,268 --> 00:32:17,383
What are you?

508
00:32:17,978 --> 00:32:19,139
I am Lumière!

509
00:32:19,271 --> 00:32:21,683
And you can talk?

510
00:32:21,857 --> 00:32:23,973
COGSWORTH:
Well, of course he can talk.

511
00:32:24,526 --> 00:32:26,142
It's all he ever does.

512
00:32:26,903 --> 00:32:29,361
Now, Lumière,
as head of the household...

513
00:32:29,489 --> 00:32:31,300
I demand that you put her
back in her cell at once.

514
00:32:31,324 --> 00:32:33,594
What do you want to be
for the rest of your life, Cogsworth?

515
00:32:33,618 --> 00:32:35,325
A man, or a mantle clock?

516
00:32:36,163 --> 00:32:37,278
Ready, miss?

517
00:32:37,581 --> 00:32:39,572
- Trust me.
- COGSWORTH: Oh...

518
00:32:41,418 --> 00:32:43,830
LUMIÈRE: You must forgive
first impressions.

519
00:32:44,004 --> 00:32:45,244
I hope you are
not too startled.

520
00:32:45,338 --> 00:32:47,170
BELLE:
Why would I be startled?

521
00:32:47,299 --> 00:32:48,299
I'm talking to a candle.

522
00:32:48,383 --> 00:32:49,999
Candelabra, please.

523
00:32:50,177 --> 00:32:51,417
Enormous difference.

524
00:32:51,511 --> 00:32:53,991
But consider me at your service.
The castle is your home now...

525
00:32:54,097 --> 00:32:55,963
so feel free to go
anywhere you like.

526
00:32:56,516 --> 00:32:58,006
Except the west wing.

527
00:32:59,686 --> 00:33:01,347
Which we do not have.

528
00:33:01,480 --> 00:33:03,938
Why? What's in the west wing?

529
00:33:04,107 --> 00:33:05,251
- Oh, nothing.
- COGSWORTH: Nothing.

530
00:33:05,275 --> 00:33:06,627
- Storage space.
- COGSWORTH: Storage space.

531
00:33:06,651 --> 00:33:07,837
- That's it.
- COGSWORTH: That's it.

532
00:33:07,861 --> 00:33:08,861
Yes, that's it.

533
00:33:08,987 --> 00:33:10,548
COGSWORTH: This way, please.
To the east wing.

534
00:33:10,572 --> 00:33:14,406
LUMIÈRE: Or as I like to call it,
the only wing. (LAUGHS)

535
00:33:14,493 --> 00:33:16,609
Watch your step,
<i>s'il vous plaít!</i>

536
00:33:21,041 --> 00:33:22,577
(BOTH EXCLAIM)

537
00:33:25,504 --> 00:33:27,586
Welcome to your new home.

538
00:33:27,714 --> 00:33:29,500
It's modest, but comfortable.

539
00:33:45,857 --> 00:33:47,643
It's beautiful.

540
00:33:47,817 --> 00:33:49,103
LUMIÈRE: But of course!

541
00:33:49,236 --> 00:33:51,728
Master wanted you to have
the finest room in the castle.

542
00:33:53,031 --> 00:33:55,568
(COUGHS) Oh, dear.
We were not expecting guests.

543
00:33:56,326 --> 00:33:58,488
PLUMETTE:
<i>Enchantée, mademoiselle.</i>

544
00:33:59,079 --> 00:34:00,285
Don't worry.

545
00:34:00,413 --> 00:34:03,155
I'll have this place spotless
in no time.

546
00:34:06,378 --> 00:34:08,585
This plan of yours
is dangerous.

547
00:34:08,755 --> 00:34:11,793
I would risk anything
to kiss you again, Plumette.

548
00:34:11,925 --> 00:34:14,508
No, my love. I've been
burned by you before.

549
00:34:14,594 --> 00:34:15,594
We must be strong.

550
00:34:15,679 --> 00:34:18,046
How can I be strong
when you make me so weak?

551
00:34:18,181 --> 00:34:19,181
(COUGHS)

552
00:34:20,767 --> 00:34:21,767
(SNORING)

553
00:34:24,145 --> 00:34:25,681
Is everything here alive?

554
00:34:26,273 --> 00:34:28,230
Hello. What's your name?

555
00:34:29,109 --> 00:34:32,192
- (BOTH LAUGH)
- That is a hairbrush.

556
00:34:33,738 --> 00:34:34,853
(HIGH PITCH VOCALIZATION)

557
00:34:36,533 --> 00:34:38,115
Do not be alarmed.

558
00:34:38,243 --> 00:34:39,358
This is just your wardrobe.

559
00:34:39,536 --> 00:34:43,074
Meet Madame De Garderobe.
A great singer.

560
00:34:43,164 --> 00:34:44,746
When she can stay awake.

561
00:34:44,833 --> 00:34:49,543
Cogsworth! A diva needs
her beauty rest. (YAWNS)

562
00:34:49,629 --> 00:34:51,711
Stay with us, Madame.

563
00:34:51,798 --> 00:34:53,288
We have someone
for you to dress!

564
00:34:53,425 --> 00:34:55,632
(GASPS) Finally...

565
00:34:55,802 --> 00:34:57,793
a woman.

566
00:34:57,887 --> 00:34:59,969
Pretty eyes.

567
00:35:00,056 --> 00:35:01,056
Proud face.

568
00:35:01,099 --> 00:35:02,965
Perfect canvas. Yes!

569
00:35:03,101 --> 00:35:06,469
I will find you something
worthy of a princess.

570
00:35:06,563 --> 00:35:07,678
Oh, I'm not a princess.

571
00:35:07,856 --> 00:35:08,971
Nonsense!

572
00:35:09,107 --> 00:35:11,815
Now, let's see
what I've got in my drawers.

573
00:35:12,235 --> 00:35:13,521
- (GASPS)
- Oh!

574
00:35:13,612 --> 00:35:14,977
How embarrassing.

575
00:35:16,239 --> 00:35:18,025
Froufrou, come help Mama.

576
00:35:18,158 --> 00:35:19,865
(BARKING)

577
00:35:25,874 --> 00:35:26,874
(GASPS)

578
00:35:28,668 --> 00:35:31,251
(EXCLAIMS IN SPANISH)

579
00:35:31,338 --> 00:35:33,454
Subtle. Understated.
I love it!

580
00:35:33,548 --> 00:35:34,709
(BIDS GOODBYE IN FRENCH)

581
00:35:34,799 --> 00:35:38,008
Froufrou, send my love
to the maestro.

582
00:35:38,511 --> 00:35:39,511
(SNORING)

583
00:36:12,379 --> 00:36:14,040
GASTON: Picture it, LeFou.

584
00:36:14,172 --> 00:36:15,583
A rustic cabin...

585
00:36:15,715 --> 00:36:18,332
my latest kill
roasting on the fire...

586
00:36:18,426 --> 00:36:21,384
adorable children running
around us as my love...

587
00:36:21,971 --> 00:36:23,678
rubs my tired feet.

588
00:36:23,765 --> 00:36:25,597
But what does Belle say?

589
00:36:25,767 --> 00:36:28,225
"I will never marry you,
Gaston!"

590
00:36:28,395 --> 00:36:30,807
You know,
there are other girls.

591
00:36:32,399 --> 00:36:34,686
A great hunter doesn't
waste his time on rabbits.

592
00:36:34,859 --> 00:36:37,897
♪ (SINGING) <i>Gosh it disturbs me ♪
♪ to see you, Gaston</i> ♪

593
00:36:38,071 --> 00:36:40,062
♪ <i>Looking so down in the dumps</i> ♪

594
00:36:41,491 --> 00:36:44,404
♪ <i>Every guy here'd ♪
♪ love to be you, Gaston</i> ♪

595
00:36:44,577 --> 00:36:47,535
♪ <i>Even when taking your lumps</i> ♪

596
00:36:47,622 --> 00:36:50,535
♪ <i>There's no man in town ♪
♪ as admired as you</i> ♪

597
00:36:50,625 --> 00:36:53,617
♪ <i>You're everyone's favorite guy</i> ♪

598
00:36:54,295 --> 00:36:58,004
♪ <i>Everyone's awed ♪
♪ and inspired by you</i> ♪

599
00:36:58,174 --> 00:37:03,760
♪ <i>And it's not very hard ♪
♪ to see why</i> ♪

600
00:37:05,932 --> 00:37:09,800
♪ <i>No one's slick as Gaston</i> ♪

601
00:37:09,936 --> 00:37:11,597
♪ <i>No one's quick as Gaston</i> ♪

602
00:37:11,730 --> 00:37:15,189
♪ <i>No one's neck's as ♪
♪ incredibly thick as Gaston</i> ♪

603
00:37:15,358 --> 00:37:18,692
♪ <i>For there's no man in town ♪
♪ half as manly</i> ♪

604
00:37:18,778 --> 00:37:22,112
♪ <i>Perfect, a pure paragon</i> ♪

605
00:37:22,240 --> 00:37:25,107
♪ <i>You can ask ♪
♪ any Tom, Dick, or Stanley</i> ♪

606
00:37:25,285 --> 00:37:30,280
♪ <i>And they'll tell you ♪
♪ whose team they prefer to be on</i> ♪

607
00:37:30,457 --> 00:37:35,372
♪ <i>Who plays</i> ♪

608
00:37:35,545 --> 00:37:36,545
♪ <i>Darts like Gaston?</i> ♪

609
00:37:36,713 --> 00:37:38,454
♪ <i>- Who breaks ♪
♪ - Hearts like Gaston?</i> ♪

610
00:37:38,548 --> 00:37:41,415
♪ <i>Who's much more than the sum ♪
♪ of his parts like Gaston?</i> ♪

611
00:37:41,551 --> 00:37:45,761
♪ <i>As a specimen, ♪
♪ yes, I'm intimidating</i> ♪

612
00:37:45,847 --> 00:37:48,965
♪ <i>My, what a guy, ♪
♪ that Gaston</i> ♪

613
00:37:49,100 --> 00:37:50,465
♪ <i>I needed encouragement</i> ♪

614
00:37:50,602 --> 00:37:51,967
♪ <i>Thank you, LeFou</i> ♪

615
00:37:52,061 --> 00:37:56,350
♪ <i>Well, there's no one ♪
♪ As easy to bolster as you</i> ♪

616
00:37:58,318 --> 00:37:59,399
Too much?

617
00:37:59,569 --> 00:38:00,775
Yep!

618
00:38:00,862 --> 00:38:05,151
♪ <i>No one fights like Gaston</i> ♪

619
00:38:05,325 --> 00:38:06,907
♪ <i>Douses lights like Gaston</i> ♪

620
00:38:07,076 --> 00:38:10,819
♪ <i>In a wrestling match ♪
♪ Nobody bites like Gaston</i> ♪

621
00:38:10,955 --> 00:38:13,492
♪ <i>When I hunt, ♪
♪ I sneak up with my quiver</i> ♪

622
00:38:14,459 --> 00:38:16,575
♪ <i>And beasts of the field ♪
♪ say a prayer</i> ♪

623
00:38:17,462 --> 00:38:18,462
Aah...

624
00:38:18,922 --> 00:38:22,506
♪ <i>First I carefully aim for the liver</i> ♪

625
00:38:22,592 --> 00:38:23,694
♪ <i>Then I shoot from behind</i> ♪

626
00:38:23,718 --> 00:38:24,799
♪ <i>Is that fair?</i> ♪

627
00:38:24,886 --> 00:38:26,251
♪ <i>I don't care</i> ♪

628
00:38:27,430 --> 00:38:29,046
♪ <i>No one hits like Gaston</i> ♪

629
00:38:29,140 --> 00:38:30,471
♪ <i>Matches wits like Gaston</i> ♪

630
00:38:30,558 --> 00:38:34,426
♪ <i>In a spitting match ♪
♪ nobody spits like Gaston</i> ♪

631
00:38:34,521 --> 00:38:38,059
♪ <i>I'm especially good ♪
♪ at expectorating</i> ♪

632
00:38:39,192 --> 00:38:40,978
ALL: Ooh!

633
00:38:41,861 --> 00:38:43,693
♪ <i>Ten points for Gaston!</i> ♪

634
00:38:43,780 --> 00:38:45,521
Thank you. Thank you.

635
00:38:46,199 --> 00:38:49,317
<i>When I was a lad
I ate four dozen eggs</i>

636
00:38:49,410 --> 00:38:52,118
♪ <i>Every morning ♪
♪ to help me get large</i> ♪

637
00:38:52,872 --> 00:38:56,035
♪ <i>And now that I'm grown ♪
♪ I eat five dozen eggs</i> ♪

638
00:38:56,209 --> 00:39:00,203
♪ <i>So I'm roughly ♪
♪ the size of a barge</i> ♪

639
00:39:01,631 --> 00:39:02,631
(GIRLS SQUEAL)

640
00:39:05,718 --> 00:39:08,676
- (ALL CLAPPING RHYTHMICALLY)
- ALL: Hey! Hey!

641
00:39:08,805 --> 00:39:09,886
Hey!

642
00:39:10,056 --> 00:39:11,056
Hey!

643
00:39:11,182 --> 00:39:12,263
- Hey!
- (SIGHS)

644
00:39:12,392 --> 00:39:13,632
Hey!

645
00:39:13,726 --> 00:39:14,807
Hey!

646
00:39:14,894 --> 00:39:15,894
Hey!

647
00:39:16,020 --> 00:39:17,886
Hey! Hey!

648
00:39:18,064 --> 00:39:20,101
Hey! Hey! Hey!

649
00:39:20,233 --> 00:39:22,395
(ALL WHOOPING AND CHEERING)

650
00:39:36,207 --> 00:39:38,494
(YELLS AND GRUNTS)

651
00:39:38,585 --> 00:39:39,825
(EXCLAIMS)

652
00:39:41,004 --> 00:39:42,085
(MAN YELLS)

653
00:39:42,630 --> 00:39:43,870
(GRUNTING)

654
00:39:43,965 --> 00:39:45,330
(GROANS)

655
00:39:48,761 --> 00:39:51,173
(MEN GROANING)

656
00:39:51,973 --> 00:39:53,634
(ALL CHEERING)

657
00:39:54,809 --> 00:39:56,049
(GIGGLING SHRILLY)

658
00:40:01,274 --> 00:40:04,107
♪ <i>Who has brains</i> ♪

659
00:40:04,193 --> 00:40:05,193
♪ <i>Like Gaston</i> ♪

660
00:40:05,361 --> 00:40:06,772
♪ <i>- Entertains ♪
♪ - Like Gaston</i> ♪

661
00:40:06,946 --> 00:40:11,986
♪ <i>Who can make up ♪
♪ these endless refrains like Gaston</i> ♪

662
00:40:13,286 --> 00:40:19,703
♪ <i>I use antlers ♪
♪ in all of my decorating</i> ♪

663
00:40:19,792 --> 00:40:21,624
♪ <i>Say it again</i> ♪

664
00:40:22,503 --> 00:40:24,414
♪ <i>Who's a man among men?</i> ♪

665
00:40:25,840 --> 00:40:27,422
♪ <i>Who's a super success?</i> ♪

666
00:40:27,508 --> 00:40:29,068
♪ <i>Don't you know? ♪
♪ Can't you guess?</i> ♪

667
00:40:29,135 --> 00:40:32,127
♪ <i>Ask his fans ♪
♪ and his five hangers-on</i> ♪

668
00:40:32,305 --> 00:40:38,347
♪ <i>There's just one guy in town ♪
♪ Who's got all of it down</i> ♪

669
00:40:39,562 --> 00:40:45,308
♪ <i>And his name's, G-A-S-T</i> ♪

670
00:40:45,485 --> 00:40:47,897
♪ <i>I believe there's another 'T'</i> ♪

671
00:40:49,155 --> 00:40:52,022
♪ <i>It just occurred to me ♪
♪ that I'm illiterate</i> ♪

672
00:40:52,200 --> 00:40:56,535
♪ <i>And I've never actually had ♪
♪ to spell it out loud before</i> ♪

673
00:40:56,704 --> 00:40:59,913
♪ <i>Gaston</i> ♪

674
00:41:03,252 --> 00:41:05,334
(ALL CHEERING)

675
00:41:07,590 --> 00:41:08,625
(LAUGHS)

676
00:41:08,716 --> 00:41:11,174
Oh, LeFou, you're the best.

677
00:41:11,302 --> 00:41:13,509
How is it no girl
has snatched you up yet?

678
00:41:13,638 --> 00:41:17,051
I've been told I'm clingy,
but I really don't get it.

679
00:41:22,563 --> 00:41:25,100
Please, please.
Someone, someone.

680
00:41:25,984 --> 00:41:27,474
- You, help...
- Whoa, whoa.

681
00:41:27,568 --> 00:41:28,729
You must help me.

682
00:41:28,861 --> 00:41:30,477
It's Belle!
He's got, he's got Belle.

683
00:41:30,571 --> 00:41:31,777
She's locked in a dungeon.

684
00:41:31,864 --> 00:41:33,195
TAVERN KEEPER: Who's got her?

685
00:41:33,324 --> 00:41:34,155
A beast!

686
00:41:34,283 --> 00:41:38,072
A huge, horrid,
monstrous beast!

687
00:41:38,162 --> 00:41:39,162
(LAUGHTER)

688
00:41:39,872 --> 00:41:41,533
My daughter's life
is in danger.

689
00:41:41,624 --> 00:41:43,911
Why do you laugh?
It's not a joke.

690
00:41:44,043 --> 00:41:47,877
His castle is hidden
in the woods.

691
00:41:48,923 --> 00:41:50,960
It's already winter there.

692
00:41:51,050 --> 00:41:52,882
Winter in June?

693
00:41:53,052 --> 00:41:54,668
- (ALL LAUGH)
- Crazy old Maurice!

694
00:41:54,762 --> 00:41:56,719
Listen to me!

695
00:41:57,557 --> 00:42:00,424
The beast is real.

696
00:42:01,561 --> 00:42:04,804
Do you understand?

697
00:42:04,897 --> 00:42:07,229
Will no one help me?

698
00:42:07,400 --> 00:42:08,515
I'll help, Maurice.

699
00:42:08,693 --> 00:42:09,693
What?

700
00:42:09,777 --> 00:42:11,188
You will?

701
00:42:11,362 --> 00:42:12,602
Everybody...

702
00:42:13,573 --> 00:42:15,905
stop making fun of this man at once.

703
00:42:16,034 --> 00:42:17,695
Captain, thank you.

704
00:42:17,785 --> 00:42:19,776
Don't thank me, Maurice.

705
00:42:19,954 --> 00:42:21,695
Lead us to the beast.

706
00:42:24,042 --> 00:42:25,042
(PANTING)

707
00:42:25,126 --> 00:42:26,457
Come.

708
00:42:27,754 --> 00:42:28,754
Hmm.

709
00:42:30,757 --> 00:42:31,757
Oh.

710
00:42:32,425 --> 00:42:34,211
Mama! There's a girl in the castle!

711
00:42:34,302 --> 00:42:35,918
Yes, Chip, we know!

712
00:42:36,054 --> 00:42:37,114
What kind of tea
does she like?

713
00:42:37,138 --> 00:42:38,924
Herbal, oolong...

714
00:42:39,015 --> 00:42:40,255
chamomile...

715
00:42:40,433 --> 00:42:41,433
I'm too excited!

716
00:42:41,559 --> 00:42:44,267
Slow down before
you break your handle.

717
00:42:44,437 --> 00:42:45,768
- Heads up, Mrs. Potts.
- Oh.

718
00:43:02,747 --> 00:43:03,747
(GRUNTS)

719
00:43:04,624 --> 00:43:05,624
THE BEAST: Lumière!

720
00:43:06,292 --> 00:43:08,292
- COGSWORTH: Oh!
- Be calm. Let me do the talking.

721
00:43:09,128 --> 00:43:10,459
You're making her dinner!

722
00:43:10,630 --> 00:43:12,590
Well, we thought you might
appreciate the company.

723
00:43:12,632 --> 00:43:14,839
Master, I just want
to assure you...

724
00:43:14,967 --> 00:43:16,799
that I had no part
in this hopeless plan.

725
00:43:16,969 --> 00:43:20,963
Preparing a dinner, designing
a gown for her, giving her...

726
00:43:21,099 --> 00:43:22,464
a suite in the east wing!

727
00:43:22,642 --> 00:43:24,349
You gave her a bedroom?

728
00:43:24,477 --> 00:43:25,967
No, no, no.
He gave her a bedroom.

729
00:43:26,145 --> 00:43:27,260
This is true.

730
00:43:27,355 --> 00:43:29,291
But if this girl is the one
who can break the spell...

731
00:43:29,315 --> 00:43:32,023
then maybe you could start
by using dinner to charm her.

732
00:43:32,193 --> 00:43:34,355
- Good thinking, Cogsworth.
- What?

733
00:43:34,487 --> 00:43:35,714
That's the most
ridiculous idea...

734
00:43:35,738 --> 00:43:37,820
I've ever heard.
Charm the prisoner!

735
00:43:37,990 --> 00:43:40,652
But you must try, Master.
With every passing day...

736
00:43:40,785 --> 00:43:42,776
we become less human.

737
00:43:42,912 --> 00:43:45,199
She's the daughter
of a common thief.

738
00:43:45,373 --> 00:43:46,975
What kind of person do you
think that makes her?

739
00:43:46,999 --> 00:43:48,831
Oh, you can't judge people...

740
00:43:48,918 --> 00:43:51,159
by who their father is,
now can you?

741
00:43:55,633 --> 00:43:57,215
You'll join me for dinner.

742
00:43:57,343 --> 00:43:58,674
That's not a request.

743
00:43:58,845 --> 00:44:00,176
Gently, Master.

744
00:44:00,263 --> 00:44:01,799
The girl lost her father...

745
00:44:01,889 --> 00:44:03,675
and her freedom in one day.

746
00:44:03,850 --> 00:44:06,512
Yes, the poor thing is probably in there,
scared to death.

747
00:44:06,686 --> 00:44:07,847
MRS. POTTS: Exactly.

748
00:44:16,529 --> 00:44:18,190
Just a minute.

749
00:44:18,322 --> 00:44:21,735
You see? There she is.
Now, remember, be gentle.

750
00:44:21,909 --> 00:44:23,820
- Kind!
- Charming!

751
00:44:23,911 --> 00:44:24,696
Sweet!

752
00:44:24,787 --> 00:44:26,198
And when she opens the door,

753
00:44:26,289 --> 00:44:29,077
give her a dashing,
debonair smile.

754
00:44:29,208 --> 00:44:30,494
Come, come. Show me the smile.

755
00:44:32,044 --> 00:44:33,205
- Oh, <i>mon dieu!</i>
- Oh, no.

756
00:44:38,718 --> 00:44:41,050
Will you join me for dinner?

757
00:44:43,764 --> 00:44:45,346
You've taken me
as your prisoner

758
00:44:45,433 --> 00:44:47,720
and now you want
to have dinner with me?

759
00:44:48,269 --> 00:44:49,555
Are you insane?

760
00:44:50,354 --> 00:44:52,391
- (GRUNTING)
- Uh-oh. He's losing it.

761
00:44:52,523 --> 00:44:53,888
Oh, dear!

762
00:44:56,569 --> 00:44:58,776
I told you
to join me for dinner.

763
00:44:58,905 --> 00:45:00,395
And I told you no.

764
00:45:00,698 --> 00:45:03,110
Ooh! What time is it?

765
00:45:03,242 --> 00:45:04,357
What's happening?

766
00:45:04,535 --> 00:45:07,527
I'd starve before
I ever ate with you.

767
00:45:07,622 --> 00:45:08,862
Well, be my guest.

768
00:45:08,956 --> 00:45:10,697
Go ahead and starve.

769
00:45:12,710 --> 00:45:14,200
If she doesn't eat with me...

770
00:45:14,295 --> 00:45:15,706
then she doesn't eat at all.

771
00:45:16,547 --> 00:45:17,708
Idiots!

772
00:45:19,258 --> 00:45:21,670
You can't talk to us
like that. I forbid it.

773
00:45:22,094 --> 00:45:24,756
Uh... Oh. Am I too late?

774
00:45:24,931 --> 00:45:27,423
Shame, I was really going to
tell him off this time.

775
00:45:27,600 --> 00:45:29,682
Oh, Master, you've returned.

776
00:45:29,769 --> 00:45:31,680
- (EXCLAIMS)
- (LAUGHS)

777
00:45:31,854 --> 00:45:33,686
- Oh, very funny.
- I got you there.

778
00:45:53,251 --> 00:45:54,912
Show me the girl.

779
00:46:25,324 --> 00:46:27,361
(RUMBLING)

780
00:46:31,414 --> 00:46:32,654
Another petal fell.

781
00:46:32,832 --> 00:46:33,832
Lumière...

782
00:46:34,500 --> 00:46:37,834
I grew three more feathers.
And I just plucked yesterday.

783
00:46:37,962 --> 00:46:39,999
I know, darling.
(EXCLAIMS)

784
00:46:40,673 --> 00:46:43,506
I'm getting more
metallic every day.

785
00:46:43,592 --> 00:46:47,756
Oh, no. It's happening again.
Pardon me.

786
00:46:47,930 --> 00:46:49,921
Oh, everyone, calm yourselves.

787
00:46:50,099 --> 00:46:53,057
- We still have time.
- Mama...

788
00:46:53,185 --> 00:46:55,597
am I ever going
to be a boy again?

789
00:46:55,688 --> 00:46:58,225
Oh, yes, Chip.
You'll have your days...

790
00:46:58,357 --> 00:47:01,145
in the sun again.
You just leave it to me.

791
00:47:08,242 --> 00:47:09,242
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

792
00:47:11,203 --> 00:47:12,864
I told you to go away.

793
00:47:12,997 --> 00:47:15,785
Don't worry, dear.
It's only Mrs. Potts.

794
00:47:24,717 --> 00:47:25,717
Oh!

795
00:47:25,968 --> 00:47:27,458
Oh, aren't you a vision!

796
00:47:27,636 --> 00:47:28,636
How lovely...

797
00:47:28,721 --> 00:47:31,008
to make your acquaintance.

798
00:47:33,893 --> 00:47:37,227
It's a very long journey.
Let me fix you up...

799
00:47:37,313 --> 00:47:38,678
before you go.

800
00:47:38,856 --> 00:47:39,937
I have found...

801
00:47:40,066 --> 00:47:42,524
that most troubles
seem less troubling...

802
00:47:42,610 --> 00:47:45,693
after a bracing cup of tea.

803
00:47:45,780 --> 00:47:47,270
Slowly now, Chip.

804
00:47:52,411 --> 00:47:53,411
(CHIP GIGGLES)

805
00:47:54,246 --> 00:47:55,246
Pleased to meet you.

806
00:47:56,290 --> 00:47:57,655
Wanna see me do a trick?

807
00:47:59,502 --> 00:48:00,502
Chip!

808
00:48:01,087 --> 00:48:05,172
That was a very brave thing
you did for your father, dearie.

809
00:48:05,341 --> 00:48:06,923
Yes.

810
00:48:07,009 --> 00:48:08,545
We all think so.

811
00:48:08,719 --> 00:48:09,925
I'm worried about him.

812
00:48:10,596 --> 00:48:13,054
He's never been on his own.

813
00:48:13,224 --> 00:48:14,931
Cheer up, my poppet.

814
00:48:15,101 --> 00:48:17,433
Things will turn out
in the end.

815
00:48:17,520 --> 00:48:18,851
You'll feel a lot better...

816
00:48:18,938 --> 00:48:20,349
after dinner.

817
00:48:20,523 --> 00:48:22,230
But he said,
"If she doesn't eat with me,

818
00:48:22,316 --> 00:48:23,727
then she doesn't eat at all."

819
00:48:24,151 --> 00:48:26,643
Mmm, people say
a lot of things in anger.

820
00:48:26,779 --> 00:48:28,736
It is our choice
whether or not to listen.

821
00:48:29,281 --> 00:48:30,362
You coming, poppet?

822
00:48:30,950 --> 00:48:31,950
Go!

823
00:48:32,576 --> 00:48:35,364
They are coming. Final checks,
everyone! <i>Tout de suite!</i>

824
00:48:35,538 --> 00:48:36,538
No, you don't!

825
00:48:36,622 --> 00:48:38,488
If the master finds out
you violated his orders

826
00:48:38,582 --> 00:48:40,072
and fed her he will blame me!

827
00:48:40,251 --> 00:48:41,537
Yes, I will make sure of it.

828
00:48:41,627 --> 00:48:43,368
But did you see her
stand up to him?

829
00:48:43,462 --> 00:48:45,248
I am telling you,
this girl is the one.

830
00:48:45,423 --> 00:48:47,503
They must fall in love
if we are to be human again...

831
00:48:47,591 --> 00:48:49,751
and how can they fall in love
if she stays in her room?

832
00:48:49,802 --> 00:48:51,463
Hey, Chapeau,
you missed a spot.

833
00:48:51,637 --> 00:48:53,127
You know
she'll never love him.

834
00:48:53,305 --> 00:48:56,218
A broken clock is right
two times a day, <i>mon ami...</i>

835
00:48:56,308 --> 00:48:58,120
but this is not one of those times.
Stand up straight!

836
00:48:58,144 --> 00:48:59,760
It's time to sparkle!

837
00:48:59,937 --> 00:49:01,644
Mmm! I have no taste buds,

838
00:49:01,730 --> 00:49:03,220
but I can tell this is exquisite.

839
00:49:03,399 --> 00:49:05,140
Off! Off me while I work!

840
00:49:05,317 --> 00:49:07,399
Pepper, get cracking!
Salt, shake a leg!

841
00:49:07,570 --> 00:49:10,483
Not so loud! Keep it down.

842
00:49:10,656 --> 00:49:12,772
Of course, of course!
But what is dinner...

843
00:49:12,867 --> 00:49:14,483
without a little music?

844
00:49:14,660 --> 00:49:15,660
Music?

845
00:49:15,828 --> 00:49:18,490
Maestro Cadenza,
are you ready?

846
00:49:18,706 --> 00:49:19,746
(MAESTRO CADENZA CHUCKLES)

847
00:49:20,541 --> 00:49:22,908
It has been so long
since I have performed.

848
00:49:23,085 --> 00:49:25,497
I can barely even
remember how.

849
00:49:25,629 --> 00:49:28,121
(PLAYS CHORDS
AND STOPS ABRUPTLY)

850
00:49:28,215 --> 00:49:29,831
- Ah!
- Ooh!

851
00:49:31,260 --> 00:49:32,500
Another cavity.

852
00:49:32,636 --> 00:49:34,422
Maestro,
your wife is upstairs...

853
00:49:34,597 --> 00:49:37,009
finding it harder and harder
to stay awake.

854
00:49:37,183 --> 00:49:40,050
She's counting on you
to help us break this curse.

855
00:49:40,186 --> 00:49:43,178
Then I shall
play through the dental pain.

856
00:49:43,314 --> 00:49:45,851
Maestro, play quietly, please.

857
00:49:46,525 --> 00:49:48,857
Oh, quietly.
Sotto voce! Of course!

858
00:49:49,028 --> 00:49:51,315
Are there any other
tasteless demands...

859
00:49:51,405 --> 00:49:52,725
you wish to make upon
my artistry?

860
00:49:53,365 --> 00:49:54,480
No, that's it.

861
00:49:54,658 --> 00:49:56,569
MRS. POTTS:
There you are, dear.

862
00:50:06,629 --> 00:50:08,461
<i>Ma chère mademoiselle.</i>

863
00:50:08,631 --> 00:50:10,372
It is with deepest pride

864
00:50:10,466 --> 00:50:11,251
and greatest pleasure...

865
00:50:11,383 --> 00:50:13,215
that we welcome you tonight.
(CLEARS THROAT)

866
00:50:13,385 --> 00:50:15,592
Here! And now...

867
00:50:15,721 --> 00:50:17,837
we invite you to relax.

868
00:50:19,141 --> 00:50:20,597
Let us pull up a chair...

869
00:50:21,644 --> 00:50:25,228
as the dining room
proudly presents...

870
00:50:27,233 --> 00:50:29,349
♪ (MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

871
00:50:32,446 --> 00:50:34,286
- (STOPS ABRUPTLY)
- (MAESTRO CADENZA EXCLAIMS)

872
00:50:35,324 --> 00:50:37,281
Your dinner!

873
00:50:37,409 --> 00:50:38,740
♪ (MUSIC CONTINUES PLAYING) ♪

874
00:50:39,703 --> 00:50:44,743
♪ (SINGING) ♪
♪ <i>Be our guest, be our guest</i> ♪

875
00:50:44,917 --> 00:50:47,659
♪ <i>Put our service to the test</i> ♪

876
00:50:47,753 --> 00:50:50,586
♪ <i>Tie your napkin ♪
♪ 'round your neck, chèrie</i> ♪

877
00:50:50,714 --> 00:50:52,705
♪ <i>And we'll provide the rest</i> ♪

878
00:50:52,800 --> 00:50:55,667
♪ <i>Soup dujour, ♪
♪ hot hors d'oeuvres</i> ♪

879
00:50:55,761 --> 00:50:57,672
♪ <i>Why we only live to serve</i> ♪

880
00:50:57,763 --> 00:51:00,175
♪ <i>Try the gray stuff, ♪
♪ it's delicious</i> ♪

881
00:51:00,266 --> 00:51:02,849
♪ <i>Don't believe me? ♪
♪ Ask the dishes</i> ♪

882
00:51:04,895 --> 00:51:06,477
(LAUGHING)

883
00:51:06,939 --> 00:51:09,601
♪ <i>They can sing, ♪
♪ they can dance</i> ♪

884
00:51:09,775 --> 00:51:11,937
♪ <i>After all, miss, ♪
♪ this is France</i> ♪

885
00:51:12,111 --> 00:51:15,945
♪ <i>And a dinner here ♪
♪ is never second best</i> ♪

886
00:51:16,240 --> 00:51:18,823
♪ <i>Go on unfold your menu</i> ♪

887
00:51:18,951 --> 00:51:20,487
♪ <i>Take a glance ♪
♪ and then you'll</i> ♪

888
00:51:20,578 --> 00:51:23,696
♪ <i>Be our guest, ♪
♪ oui, our guest</i> ♪

889
00:51:23,789 --> 00:51:25,496
♪ <i>Be our guest</i> ♪

890
00:51:25,624 --> 00:51:26,624
Ooh!

891
00:51:29,920 --> 00:51:31,081
♪ <i>Beef ragout</i> ♪

892
00:51:31,171 --> 00:51:32,502
♪ <i>Cheese soufflé</i> ♪

893
00:51:32,631 --> 00:51:34,167
♪ <i>Pie and pudding en flambé</i> ♪

894
00:51:34,300 --> 00:51:38,134
♪ <i>We'll prepare and serve with flair ♪
♪ A culinary cabaret</i> ♪

895
00:51:38,971 --> 00:51:41,463
♪ <i>You're alone ♪
♪ and you're scared</i> ♪

896
00:51:41,557 --> 00:51:43,639
♪ <i>But the banquet's ♪
♪ all prepared</i> ♪

897
00:51:43,767 --> 00:51:45,508
♪ <i>No one's gloomy ♪
♪ or complaining</i> ♪

898
00:51:45,603 --> 00:51:47,594
♪ <i>While the flatware's ♪
♪ entertaining</i> ♪

899
00:51:47,771 --> 00:51:49,353
♪ <i>We tell jokes, I do tricks</i> ♪

900
00:51:49,481 --> 00:51:52,098
♪ <i>With my fellow candlesticks</i> ♪

901
00:51:52,192 --> 00:51:53,628
♪ CHORUS: ♪
♪ <i>And it's all in perfect taste</i> ♪

902
00:51:53,652 --> 00:51:55,768
♪ <i>That you can bet</i> ♪

903
00:51:55,904 --> 00:51:57,986
♪ <i>Come on and ♪
♪ lift your glass</i> ♪

904
00:51:58,157 --> 00:52:00,239
♪ <i>You've won your own free pass</i> ♪

905
00:52:00,326 --> 00:52:01,987
♪ <i>To be our guest</i> ♪

906
00:52:02,077 --> 00:52:04,944
♪ <i>If you're stressed ♪
♪ It's fine dining we suggest</i> ♪

907
00:52:05,039 --> 00:52:06,039
♪ <i>Be our guest</i> ♪

908
00:52:06,165 --> 00:52:11,001
♪ <i>Be our guest, ♪
♪ be our guest</i> ♪

909
00:52:11,629 --> 00:52:14,462
♪ <i>Life is so unnerving</i> ♪

910
00:52:14,548 --> 00:52:16,960
♪ <i>For a servant ♪
♪ who's not serving</i> ♪

911
00:52:17,134 --> 00:52:21,128
♪ <i>He's not whole ♪
♪ Without a soul to wait upon</i> ♪

912
00:52:21,847 --> 00:52:26,057
♪ <i>Ah, those good old days ♪
♪ when we were useful</i> ♪

913
00:52:26,185 --> 00:52:27,095
Eh, Cogsworth?

914
00:52:27,186 --> 00:52:31,430
♪ <i>Suddenly those good old days are gone</i> ♪

915
00:52:33,192 --> 00:52:36,401
♪ <i>Too long we've been rusting</i> ♪

916
00:52:36,570 --> 00:52:39,358
♪ <i>Needing so much more than dusting</i> ♪

917
00:52:39,531 --> 00:52:42,865
♪ <i>Needing exercise, ♪
♪ a chance to use our skills</i> ♪

918
00:52:42,993 --> 00:52:44,154
(GRUNTING)

919
00:52:46,789 --> 00:52:51,158
♪ <i>Most days we just lay ♪
♪ around the castle</i> ♪

920
00:52:51,335 --> 00:52:52,791
♪ <i>Flabby, fat and lazy</i> ♪

921
00:52:52,878 --> 00:52:55,085
♪ <i>You walked in ♪
♪ and whoops-a-daisy</i> ♪

922
00:52:55,214 --> 00:52:56,955
♪ <i>It's a guest, ♪
♪ it's a guest</i> ♪

923
00:52:57,049 --> 00:52:59,006
♪ <i>Sakes alive, ♪
♪ well, I'll be blessed</i> ♪

924
00:52:59,093 --> 00:53:00,959
♪ <i>Wine's been poured ♪
♪ and thank the Lord</i> ♪

925
00:53:01,053 --> 00:53:03,135
♪ <i>I've had the napkins freshly pressed</i> ♪

926
00:53:03,305 --> 00:53:05,342
♪ <i>With dessert, ♪
♪ she'll want tea</i> ♪

927
00:53:05,432 --> 00:53:07,298
♪ <i>And my dear, ♪
♪ that's fine with me</i> ♪

928
00:53:07,476 --> 00:53:09,342
♪ <i>While the cups ♪
♪ do their soft-shoeing</i> ♪

929
00:53:09,478 --> 00:53:11,970
♪ <i>I'll be bubbling, ♪
♪ I'll be brewing</i> ♪

930
00:53:13,065 --> 00:53:14,226
(ALL VOCALIZING)

931
00:53:22,574 --> 00:53:24,485
♪ <i>l'll get warm, piping hot</i> ♪

932
00:53:24,576 --> 00:53:26,237
♪ <i>Heaven's sakes, ♪
♪ is that a spot?</i> ♪

933
00:53:26,412 --> 00:53:30,155
♪ <i>Clean it up, we want ♪
♪ the company impressed</i> ♪

934
00:53:30,332 --> 00:53:32,164
♪ <i>We've got a lot to do</i> ♪

935
00:53:32,292 --> 00:53:34,374
♪ <i>Is it one lump or two?</i> ♪

936
00:53:34,503 --> 00:53:35,868
♪ <i>For you, our guest</i> ♪

937
00:53:35,963 --> 00:53:36,963
♪ <i>She's our guest</i> ♪

938
00:53:37,047 --> 00:53:38,047
♪ <i>She's our guest</i> ♪

939
00:53:38,132 --> 00:53:39,293
♪ <i>She's our guest</i> ♪

940
00:53:39,425 --> 00:53:41,211
♪ ALL: ♪
♪ <i>Be our guest, be our guest</i> ♪

941
00:53:41,301 --> 00:53:43,133
♪ <i>Our command ♪
♪ is your request</i> ♪

942
00:53:43,303 --> 00:53:46,011
♪ <i>It's been years ♪
♪ since we've had anybody</i> ♪

943
00:53:46,098 --> 00:53:47,384
♪ <i>Here and we're obsessed</i> ♪

944
00:53:47,558 --> 00:53:49,515
♪ <i>With your meal</i> ♪

945
00:53:49,643 --> 00:53:51,759
♪ <i>With your ease</i> ♪

946
00:53:51,937 --> 00:53:55,931
♪ <i>Yes indeed, ♪
♪ we aim to please</i> ♪

947
00:53:56,108 --> 00:53:58,816
♪ <i>While the candlelight's ♪
♪ still glowing</i> ♪

948
00:53:58,902 --> 00:53:59,937
(LAUGHS)

949
00:54:00,612 --> 00:54:04,276
♪ <i>Let us help you, ♪
♪ we'll keep going</i> ♪

950
00:54:07,745 --> 00:54:10,863
♪ <i>Course by</i> ♪

951
00:54:11,039 --> 00:54:14,577
♪ <i>Course! ♪
♪ One by one</i> ♪

952
00:54:14,752 --> 00:54:17,414
♪ <i>'Til you shout, ♪
♪ "Enough, I'm done!"</i> ♪

953
00:54:17,588 --> 00:54:19,545
♪ <i>Then we'll sing you off to sleep</i> ♪

954
00:54:19,631 --> 00:54:21,247
♪ <i>As you digest</i> ♪

955
00:54:21,425 --> 00:54:25,794
♪ <i>Tonight you'll prop your feet up ♪
♪ But for now let's eat up</i> ♪

956
00:54:25,929 --> 00:54:27,294
♪ <i>Be our guest</i> ♪

957
00:54:27,431 --> 00:54:28,762
♪ <i>Be our guest</i> ♪

958
00:54:29,558 --> 00:54:31,219
♪ <i>Be our guest</i> ♪

959
00:54:31,310 --> 00:54:37,477
♪ <i>Please be our guest</i> ♪

960
00:54:40,819 --> 00:54:41,479
Pudding?

961
00:54:41,820 --> 00:54:42,820
(LAUGHS)

962
00:54:45,574 --> 00:54:47,861
I don't understand why
you're all being so kind to me.

963
00:54:48,452 --> 00:54:50,693
Surely, you're as trapped
here as I am.

964
00:54:50,829 --> 00:54:52,411
Don't you ever want to escape?

965
00:54:52,581 --> 00:54:57,451
The master's not
as terrible as he appears.

966
00:54:57,544 --> 00:55:01,253
Somewhere deep in his soul,
there's a prince...

967
00:55:01,340 --> 00:55:05,459
of a fellow who just waiting
to be set free.

968
00:55:06,762 --> 00:55:09,174
Lumière mentioned something
about the west wing.

969
00:55:09,348 --> 00:55:11,840
Never you mind about that.

970
00:55:11,975 --> 00:55:13,095
Off to bed with you, poppet.

971
00:55:13,268 --> 00:55:15,475
- Good night.
- Nighty-night.

972
00:55:20,359 --> 00:55:22,020
MRS. POTTS: Straight to bed.

973
00:55:36,834 --> 00:55:37,915
(PANTING)

974
00:56:55,287 --> 00:56:57,198
What are you doing here?
What did you do to it?

975
00:56:57,289 --> 00:56:58,199
Nothing.

976
00:56:58,290 --> 00:56:59,559
Do you realize
what you could have done?

977
00:56:59,583 --> 00:57:00,948
You could have damned us all!

978
00:57:01,043 --> 00:57:02,249
Get out of here!

979
00:57:03,045 --> 00:57:04,410
Go!

980
00:57:09,718 --> 00:57:11,550
(PANTING)

981
00:57:13,555 --> 00:57:15,466
LUMIÈRE: Checkmate. Again.

982
00:57:15,557 --> 00:57:17,468
Wait! No! You cheated again.

983
00:57:17,601 --> 00:57:20,309
<i>Mademoiselle,</i>
what are you doing?

984
00:57:20,395 --> 00:57:22,136
Getting out of here.

985
00:57:22,230 --> 00:57:23,516
- Stop!
- (LUMIÈRE GRUNTS)

986
00:57:24,483 --> 00:57:25,769
Go! Go! Froufrou!

987
00:57:27,444 --> 00:57:28,900
Yes, Froufrou. Stop her.

988
00:57:29,071 --> 00:57:30,482
LUMIÈRE: Don't let her leave!

989
00:57:30,614 --> 00:57:32,230
- MRS. POTTS: Stop her!
- (BARKING)

990
00:57:32,324 --> 00:57:33,324
No! No! Froufrou!

991
00:57:33,450 --> 00:57:34,802
COGSWORTH: No!
No, it's not play time!

992
00:57:34,826 --> 00:57:36,737
LUMIÈRE: Not now, silly boy.

993
00:57:36,828 --> 00:57:38,284
COGSWORTH: Bad dog. Bad dog!

994
00:57:38,413 --> 00:57:39,995
LUMIÈRE: No! No! No!

995
00:57:40,165 --> 00:57:41,405
Please don't go!

996
00:57:41,500 --> 00:57:42,615
It's dangerous!

997
00:57:42,793 --> 00:57:44,454
Oh, my!

998
00:57:48,882 --> 00:57:49,882
(PANTING)

999
00:57:56,181 --> 00:57:57,512
(HOWLING)

1000
00:57:58,809 --> 00:58:00,925
- (GROWLS)
- (ALL HOWLING)

1001
00:58:09,027 --> 00:58:11,109
(PHILIPPE WHINNYING)

1002
00:58:11,321 --> 00:58:12,356
(GROWLING)

1003
00:58:15,617 --> 00:58:17,233
(GROWLING)

1004
00:58:26,628 --> 00:58:28,494
- (GROWLS)
- (GASPS)

1005
00:58:36,513 --> 00:58:38,129
(SNARLING)

1006
00:58:39,182 --> 00:58:42,720
(GROWLING)

1007
00:58:52,571 --> 00:58:53,902
(YELPS)

1008
00:58:55,741 --> 00:58:57,527
(GROWLING)

1009
00:59:11,548 --> 00:59:13,130
(GROWLS)

1010
00:59:13,884 --> 00:59:14,884
(GROWLING)

1011
00:59:25,020 --> 00:59:26,260
(ROARING)

1012
00:59:28,023 --> 00:59:29,809
(WOLVES HOWLING)

1013
00:59:34,112 --> 00:59:35,193
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

1014
00:59:40,786 --> 00:59:42,117
(GRUNTS)

1015
00:59:47,959 --> 00:59:50,542
(THE BEAST BREATHING HEAVILY)

1016
01:00:22,285 --> 01:00:23,565
(WHISPERING)
You have to help me.

1017
01:00:24,663 --> 01:00:26,529
You have to stand.

1018
01:00:28,875 --> 01:00:32,118
(THE BEAST BREATHING HEAVILY)

1019
01:00:40,595 --> 01:00:43,178
(WOLVES HOWLING)

1020
01:00:43,765 --> 01:00:46,132
MAURICE: No!
I'm sure this is the way.

1021
01:00:46,309 --> 01:00:47,549
Do you hear those wolves?

1022
01:00:47,727 --> 01:00:50,685
That means we're getting
very close to the castle.

1023
01:00:50,814 --> 01:00:53,522
Look, enough is enough.
We have to turn back.

1024
01:00:53,692 --> 01:00:54,557
Stop!

1025
01:00:54,693 --> 01:00:56,855
That's it! There it is!

1026
01:00:57,487 --> 01:00:59,194
That's the tree!

1027
01:00:59,322 --> 01:01:00,483
I'm sure of it.

1028
01:01:00,657 --> 01:01:04,195
It was downed
by lightning at the time.

1029
01:01:04,369 --> 01:01:06,110
But now...

1030
01:01:06,288 --> 01:01:08,120
it's resumed
an upright position...

1031
01:01:08,206 --> 01:01:09,446
through some sort of...

1032
01:01:10,125 --> 01:01:12,366
magic or other.

1033
01:01:12,460 --> 01:01:14,622
You really wanna marry
into this family?

1034
01:01:14,796 --> 01:01:15,796
So, that means...

1035
01:01:16,548 --> 01:01:17,709
that the castle is that...

1036
01:01:17,799 --> 01:01:18,799
No.

1037
01:01:19,551 --> 01:01:20,632
No, it's...

1038
01:01:21,928 --> 01:01:23,088
(WHISTLES
AND BLOWS RASPBERRY)

1039
01:01:23,221 --> 01:01:24,221
That way.

1040
01:01:24,306 --> 01:01:26,047
Definitely, that way.

1041
01:01:26,224 --> 01:01:29,433
I am done playing
this game of yours.

1042
01:01:29,603 --> 01:01:31,185
Where is Belle?

1043
01:01:31,313 --> 01:01:33,270
The beast took her and she...

1044
01:01:33,440 --> 01:01:35,556
There are no such things
as beasts.

1045
01:01:35,650 --> 01:01:37,482
Or talking teacups.

1046
01:01:37,652 --> 01:01:38,858
Or magic!

1047
01:01:39,029 --> 01:01:42,442
But there are wolves,
frostbite, and starvation.

1048
01:01:43,450 --> 01:01:45,316
Deep breaths, Gaston.

1049
01:01:45,452 --> 01:01:47,568
Deep breaths.

1050
01:01:47,787 --> 01:01:50,028
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

1051
01:01:50,165 --> 01:01:53,374
So, why don't we just turn around?
Go back to Villeneuve.

1052
01:01:53,543 --> 01:01:56,001
I'm sure Belle is at home,
cooking up a lovely dinner.

1053
01:01:56,171 --> 01:01:57,611
If you think
I've made all this up...

1054
01:01:57,714 --> 01:02:00,627
then why did you offer to help?

1055
01:02:00,759 --> 01:02:02,420
Because I want to marry
your daughter!

1056
01:02:05,096 --> 01:02:07,428
Now, let's go home.

1057
01:02:07,557 --> 01:02:09,343
Belle is not at home.

1058
01:02:09,517 --> 01:02:10,848
She is with the...

1059
01:02:11,019 --> 01:02:13,807
You say beast one more time...

1060
01:02:13,939 --> 01:02:15,771
I will feed you to the wolves!

1061
01:02:15,857 --> 01:02:18,269
Gaston! Stop it! Breathe!

1062
01:02:18,401 --> 01:02:20,517
Think happy thoughts.
Go back to the war.

1063
01:02:20,654 --> 01:02:22,065
Blood.

1064
01:02:22,155 --> 01:02:24,692
Explosions. Countless widows.

1065
01:02:24,783 --> 01:02:26,114
- Widows.
- Yes. Yes.

1066
01:02:26,243 --> 01:02:27,574
- (EXHALES)
- That's it.

1067
01:02:28,828 --> 01:02:30,444
That's it.

1068
01:02:30,622 --> 01:02:31,622
(CHUCKLES)

1069
01:02:32,791 --> 01:02:34,247
Maurice!

1070
01:02:35,377 --> 01:02:37,744
Please, forgive me, old bean.

1071
01:02:37,879 --> 01:02:40,166
That's no way to talk
to my future father-in-law...

1072
01:02:40,298 --> 01:02:41,298
now is it?

1073
01:02:41,341 --> 01:02:42,376
Future father-in-law?

1074
01:02:42,509 --> 01:02:43,509
Yeah!

1075
01:02:43,635 --> 01:02:47,720
You will never marry
my daughter.

1076
01:02:50,725 --> 01:02:52,511
(GRUNTS)

1077
01:02:53,770 --> 01:02:55,056
I saw that coming.

1078
01:02:55,772 --> 01:02:58,059
If Maurice won't
give me his blessing...

1079
01:02:58,191 --> 01:03:00,023
then he is in my way.

1080
01:03:00,193 --> 01:03:01,753
Once the wolves
are finished with him...

1081
01:03:01,778 --> 01:03:04,440
Belle will have no one
to take care of her but me.

1082
01:03:04,614 --> 01:03:06,494
For the sake of exhausting
all of our options...

1083
01:03:06,574 --> 01:03:09,032
do we maybe wanna consider
a slightly less...

1084
01:03:09,160 --> 01:03:10,776
gruesome alternative?

1085
01:03:10,870 --> 01:03:11,870
Are you coming?

1086
01:03:16,876 --> 01:03:17,876
Yah!

1087
01:03:19,004 --> 01:03:20,620
(WOLVES HOWLING IN DISTANCE)

1088
01:03:21,715 --> 01:03:23,501
(THE BEAST GROWLING IN PAIN)

1089
01:03:25,844 --> 01:03:26,844
That hurts!

1090
01:03:26,928 --> 01:03:29,795
If you held still,
it wouldn't hurt as much.

1091
01:03:29,931 --> 01:03:32,201
Well, if you hadn't run away,
none of this would have happened.

1092
01:03:32,225 --> 01:03:34,537
Well, if you hadn't frightened me,
I wouldn't have run away.

1093
01:03:34,561 --> 01:03:36,401
Well, you shouldn't have been
in the west wing.

1094
01:03:36,479 --> 01:03:39,187
Well, you should learn
to control your temper!

1095
01:03:39,357 --> 01:03:40,722
(GRUNTS)

1096
01:03:48,575 --> 01:03:51,033
Try to get some rest.

1097
01:03:51,119 --> 01:03:52,359
Thank you, miss.

1098
01:03:52,495 --> 01:03:55,032
We are eternally grateful.

1099
01:03:55,123 --> 01:03:57,615
Why do you care
about him so much?

1100
01:03:57,709 --> 01:03:59,199
We've looked after him all his life.

1101
01:04:00,128 --> 01:04:02,790
But he's cursed you somehow. Why?

1102
01:04:02,881 --> 01:04:04,042
You did nothing!

1103
01:04:04,924 --> 01:04:07,416
You're quite right there, dear.

1104
01:04:07,594 --> 01:04:10,632
You see, when the master
lost his mother...

1105
01:04:10,764 --> 01:04:13,847
and his cruel father
took that sweet, innocent lad...

1106
01:04:15,769 --> 01:04:18,056
and twisted him up
to be just like him...

1107
01:04:18,605 --> 01:04:20,642
we did nothing.

1108
01:04:20,732 --> 01:04:22,143
LUMIÈRE: Let him sleep.

1109
01:04:34,245 --> 01:04:36,577
YOUNG PRINCE: (SINGING)
♪ <i>Days in the sun</i> ♪

1110
01:04:36,748 --> 01:04:40,742
♪ <i>When my life ♪
♪ has barely begun</i> ♪

1111
01:04:40,919 --> 01:04:44,958
♪ <i>Not until ♪
♪ my whole life is done</i> ♪

1112
01:04:45,131 --> 01:04:49,125
♪ <i>Will I ever leave you</i> ♪

1113
01:05:10,740 --> 01:05:14,028
♪ <i>Will I tremble again</i> ♪

1114
01:05:14,202 --> 01:05:18,241
♪ <i>To my dear one's ♪
♪ gorgeous refrain</i> ♪

1115
01:05:18,415 --> 01:05:22,329
♪ <i>Will you now ♪
♪ forever remain</i> ♪

1116
01:05:22,502 --> 01:05:27,417
♪ <i>Out of reach of my arms</i> ♪

1117
01:05:27,507 --> 01:05:30,625
♪ <i>Oh, those days in the sun</i> ♪

1118
01:05:30,802 --> 01:05:34,841
♪ <i>What I'd give ♪
♪ to relive just one</i> ♪

1119
01:05:35,014 --> 01:05:36,345
(YAWNS) 'Night, Mama.

1120
01:05:36,516 --> 01:05:38,883
♪ <i>Undo what's done</i> ♪

1121
01:05:39,060 --> 01:05:42,678
♪ <i>And bring back the light</i> ♪

1122
01:05:43,690 --> 01:05:47,354
♪ <i>Oh, I could sing</i> ♪

1123
01:05:47,527 --> 01:05:52,567
♪ <i>Of the pain ♪
♪ these dark days bring</i> ♪

1124
01:05:52,740 --> 01:05:57,610
♪ <i>The spell we're under</i> ♪

1125
01:05:57,787 --> 01:06:02,953
♪ <i>Still it's the wonder of us ♪
♪ I sing of tonight</i> ♪

1126
01:06:03,126 --> 01:06:06,915
♪ <i>How in the midst ♪
♪ of all this sorrow</i> ♪

1127
01:06:07,088 --> 01:06:10,581
♪ <i>Can so much ♪
♪ hope and love endure</i> ♪

1128
01:06:10,758 --> 01:06:14,626
♪ <i>I was innocent and certain</i> ♪

1129
01:06:14,804 --> 01:06:18,513
♪ <i>Now I'm wiser but unsure</i> ♪

1130
01:06:18,683 --> 01:06:20,265
♪ <i>Days in the past</i> ♪

1131
01:06:20,351 --> 01:06:22,558
♪ <i>I can't go back ♪
♪ into my childhood</i> ♪

1132
01:06:22,729 --> 01:06:25,096
GARDEROBE:
♪ <i>Oh, those precious days couldn't last</i> ♪

1133
01:06:25,190 --> 01:06:27,727
♪ <i>One that my father ♪
♪ made secure</i> ♪

1134
01:06:28,610 --> 01:06:31,978
♪ <i>I can feel a change in me</i> ♪

1135
01:06:32,155 --> 01:06:34,988
GARDEROBE:
♪ <i>Oh, hold me closer</i> ♪

1136
01:06:35,074 --> 01:06:37,691
BELLE: ♪<i>I'm stronger now
but still not free</i> ♪

1137
01:06:37,869 --> 01:06:40,531
ALL:
♪ <i>Days in the sun</i> ♪

1138
01:06:40,705 --> 01:06:45,825
♪ <i>Will return ♪
♪ we must believe</i> ♪

1139
01:06:46,002 --> 01:06:50,542
♪ <i>As lovers do</i> ♪

1140
01:06:50,715 --> 01:06:53,503
♪ <i>That days in the sun</i> ♪

1141
01:06:53,676 --> 01:06:59,718
♪ <i>Will come shining through</i> ♪

1142
01:07:04,187 --> 01:07:06,394
What happens
when the last petal falls?

1143
01:07:06,481 --> 01:07:08,347
The master remains
a beast forever.

1144
01:07:08,441 --> 01:07:10,182
And we become...

1145
01:07:10,276 --> 01:07:11,937
- Antiques.
- Knick-knacks.

1146
01:07:12,111 --> 01:07:13,647
Lightly-used houseware.

1147
01:07:13,821 --> 01:07:14,821
Rubbish.

1148
01:07:14,864 --> 01:07:16,901
We become rubbish.

1149
01:07:17,617 --> 01:07:19,528
I want to help you.

1150
01:07:19,702 --> 01:07:21,784
There must be some way
to break the curse.

1151
01:07:22,413 --> 01:07:24,780
Well, there is one.

1152
01:07:24,916 --> 01:07:26,907
It's not for you
to worry about, lamb.

1153
01:07:27,085 --> 01:07:30,578
We've made our bed
and we must lie in it.

1154
01:08:02,453 --> 01:08:04,319
(MAURICE BREATHING SHAKILY)

1155
01:08:17,051 --> 01:08:18,633
(HOOTING)

1156
01:08:22,807 --> 01:08:24,047
Drink.

1157
01:08:24,309 --> 01:08:25,344
(SIPPING)

1158
01:08:27,854 --> 01:08:29,140
(EXHALES)

1159
01:08:30,648 --> 01:08:33,436
Thank you, Agathe.

1160
01:08:34,360 --> 01:08:36,818
BELLE: "Love can transpose
to form and dignity."

1161
01:08:36,988 --> 01:08:39,150
"Love looks not with the eyes"

1162
01:08:39,240 --> 01:08:41,277
"but with the mind
and therefore..."

1163
01:08:41,451 --> 01:08:45,570
"And therefore is winged Cupid
painted blind."

1164
01:08:47,665 --> 01:08:49,576
You know Shakespeare?

1165
01:08:49,709 --> 01:08:50,744
(GRUNTS)

1166
01:08:51,294 --> 01:08:53,626
I had an expensive education.

1167
01:08:54,964 --> 01:08:57,581
Actually, <i>Romeo and Juliet's</i>
my favorite play.

1168
01:08:57,800 --> 01:09:01,338
(GROANS) Why is that not a surprise?

1169
01:09:02,221 --> 01:09:03,632
I'm sorry?

1170
01:09:03,723 --> 01:09:07,637
Well, all that heartache
and pining and... (RETCHING)

1171
01:09:09,479 --> 01:09:10,679
So many better things to read.

1172
01:09:11,522 --> 01:09:12,762
Like what?

1173
01:09:13,483 --> 01:09:15,269
Well, there are a couple of...

1174
01:09:15,360 --> 01:09:18,022
things in here
you could start with.

1175
01:09:18,237 --> 01:09:19,602
(GASPS SOFTLY)

1176
01:09:21,699 --> 01:09:23,531
Are you all right?

1177
01:09:30,958 --> 01:09:33,040
It's wonderful!

1178
01:09:36,464 --> 01:09:38,831
Yes. I suppose it is.

1179
01:09:43,846 --> 01:09:46,133
Well, if you like it so much,
then it's yours.

1180
01:09:52,313 --> 01:09:54,113
Have you really read every one
of these books?

1181
01:09:54,148 --> 01:09:55,148
What?

1182
01:09:56,651 --> 01:09:59,985
(SCOFFS)
Well, not all of them.

1183
01:10:00,154 --> 01:10:02,441
Some of them are in Greek.

1184
01:10:02,573 --> 01:10:04,234
Was that a joke?

1185
01:10:05,827 --> 01:10:07,317
Are you making jokes now?

1186
01:10:09,539 --> 01:10:10,779
Maybe.

1187
01:10:11,124 --> 01:10:12,580
(BELLE CHUCKLES)

1188
01:10:25,513 --> 01:10:27,129
(SHRIEKS EXCITEDLY)

1189
01:10:28,099 --> 01:10:29,099
(LAUGHS)

1190
01:10:34,772 --> 01:10:35,772
(SLURPING)

1191
01:10:44,449 --> 01:10:48,283
BELLE: <i>"The air is blue
and keen and cold...</i>

1192
01:10:48,411 --> 01:10:51,494
"and in a frozen sheath,
enrolled."

1193
01:10:51,622 --> 01:10:53,454
"Each branch, each twig..."

1194
01:10:53,624 --> 01:10:57,458
"each blade of grass seems
clad miraculously with..."

1195
01:10:59,297 --> 01:11:00,628
"glass."

1196
01:11:01,048 --> 01:11:02,630
(BIRDS CHIRPING IN DISTANCE)

1197
01:11:07,513 --> 01:11:10,130
I feel as if I'm
seeing it for the first time.

1198
01:11:15,313 --> 01:11:16,519
Is there any more?

1199
01:11:17,231 --> 01:11:20,064
(LAUGHS) Um...

1200
01:11:22,945 --> 01:11:27,189
"But in that solemn silence
is heard the whisper..."

1201
01:11:27,325 --> 01:11:29,316
"of every sleeping thing."

1202
01:11:29,994 --> 01:11:32,406
"Look. Look at me."

1203
01:11:34,665 --> 01:11:36,872
"Come wake me up."

1204
01:11:38,669 --> 01:11:40,580
"For still here I be."

1205
01:11:50,389 --> 01:11:52,175
(NEIGHS SOFTLY)

1206
01:11:53,059 --> 01:11:54,515
(SHUSHING)

1207
01:12:09,200 --> 01:12:12,693
(SINGING) ♪<i>There's something sweet
and almost kind</i> ♪

1208
01:12:13,329 --> 01:12:17,288
♪ <i>But he was mean ♪
♪ and he was coarse and unrefined</i> ♪

1209
01:12:17,375 --> 01:12:20,709
♪ <i>And now he's dear ♪
♪ and so unsure</i> ♪

1210
01:12:20,878 --> 01:12:24,121
♪ <i>I wonder why ♪
♪ I didn't see it there before</i> ♪

1211
01:12:27,134 --> 01:12:28,670
(GRUNTS)

1212
01:12:28,928 --> 01:12:29,928
(LAUGHS)

1213
01:12:34,183 --> 01:12:35,469
(CHUCKLES)

1214
01:12:35,560 --> 01:12:39,303
♪ <i>She glanced this way ♪
♪ I thought I saw</i> ♪

1215
01:12:39,397 --> 01:12:42,890
♪ <i>And when we touched ♪
♪ She didn't shudder at my paw</i> ♪

1216
01:12:43,067 --> 01:12:46,901
♪ <i>No, it can't be ♪
♪ I'll just ignore</i> ♪

1217
01:12:47,071 --> 01:12:48,937
♪ <i>But then ♪
♪ she's never looked at me</i> ♪

1218
01:12:49,031 --> 01:12:50,521
♪ <i>That way before</i> ♪

1219
01:13:09,969 --> 01:13:11,334
(BOTH SLURPING)

1220
01:13:15,016 --> 01:13:16,472
(CHUCKLES)

1221
01:13:21,439 --> 01:13:26,934
♪ <i>New, and a bit alarming</i> ♪

1222
01:13:27,820 --> 01:13:34,408
♪ <i>Who'd have ever thought ♪
♪ that this could be</i> ♪

1223
01:13:36,913 --> 01:13:43,000
♪ <i>True that ♪
♪ he's no Prince Charming</i> ♪

1224
01:13:43,169 --> 01:13:49,211
♪ <i>But there's something in him ♪
♪ That I simply didn't see</i> ♪

1225
01:13:51,469 --> 01:13:52,529
PLUMETTE:
♪ <i>Well, who'd have thought?</i> ♪

1226
01:13:52,553 --> 01:13:53,655
MRS. POTTS:
♪ <i>Well, bless my soul!</i> ♪

1227
01:13:53,679 --> 01:13:55,574
♪ <i>- Well, who'd have known? ♪
♪ - Well, who indeed?</i> ♪

1228
01:13:55,598 --> 01:13:56,838
♪ <i>And who'd have guessed</i> ♪

1229
01:13:56,933 --> 01:13:58,640
♪ <i>They'd come together on their own</i> ♪

1230
01:13:58,768 --> 01:14:00,488
MRS. POTTS: ♪<i>It's so peculiar
Wait and see</i> ♪

1231
01:14:00,519 --> 01:14:03,227
ALL: ♪<i>We'll wait and see
A few days more</i> ♪

1232
01:14:03,397 --> 01:14:06,685
♪ <i>There may be something there ♪
♪ That wasn't there before</i> ♪

1233
01:14:07,276 --> 01:14:09,062
And here's a thought...

1234
01:14:09,236 --> 01:14:11,022
♪ <i>Perhaps there's something there</i> ♪

1235
01:14:11,113 --> 01:14:12,649
♪ <i>That wasn't there before</i> ♪

1236
01:14:12,823 --> 01:14:14,814
- (PLUMETTE CHUCKLES)
- CHIP: What, Mama?

1237
01:14:15,826 --> 01:14:21,822
♪ <i>There may be something there ♪
♪ That wasn't there before</i> ♪

1238
01:14:23,167 --> 01:14:25,534
What is it? What's there?

1239
01:14:25,753 --> 01:14:28,211
I'll tell you
when you're older.

1240
01:14:29,173 --> 01:14:31,164
Okay, I'm older!

1241
01:14:31,467 --> 01:14:33,253
(SCOFFS) Chip...

1242
01:14:33,344 --> 01:14:36,427
(LAUGHING) You are a one.

1243
01:14:50,903 --> 01:14:52,485
What are you reading?

1244
01:14:52,655 --> 01:14:53,655
Nothing.

1245
01:14:54,949 --> 01:14:56,610
<i>Guinevere and Lancelot.</i>

1246
01:14:56,784 --> 01:14:58,445
Well, actually...

1247
01:14:58,619 --> 01:15:00,906
<i>King Arthur
and the Round Table.</i>

1248
01:15:01,080 --> 01:15:04,038
Knights and men
and swords and things.

1249
01:15:04,291 --> 01:15:05,291
Mmm.

1250
01:15:05,584 --> 01:15:06,870
Still...

1251
01:15:07,503 --> 01:15:08,584
it's a romance.

1252
01:15:08,713 --> 01:15:09,919
All right.

1253
01:15:13,509 --> 01:15:16,092
I never thanked you
for saving my life.

1254
01:15:16,679 --> 01:15:18,465
Well, I never thanked you...

1255
01:15:18,639 --> 01:15:21,381
for not leaving me
to be eaten by wolves.

1256
01:15:21,559 --> 01:15:22,890
(LAUGHS)

1257
01:15:22,977 --> 01:15:24,308
(ALL CHATTERING EXCITEDLY)

1258
01:15:25,396 --> 01:15:26,996
BELLE: They know
how to have a good time.

1259
01:15:27,148 --> 01:15:31,233
Yes. But when I enter the room,
laughter dies.

1260
01:15:32,069 --> 01:15:33,400
Me too.

1261
01:15:35,364 --> 01:15:37,856
The villagers say that
I'm a funny girl...

1262
01:15:37,950 --> 01:15:40,032
but I'm not sure they mean it
as a compliment.

1263
01:15:40,202 --> 01:15:41,202
I'm sorry.

1264
01:15:42,538 --> 01:15:44,575
Your village sounds terrible.

1265
01:15:44,790 --> 01:15:47,122
(SIGHS) Almost as lonely
as your castle.

1266
01:15:49,170 --> 01:15:51,787
What do you say we run away?

1267
01:16:03,809 --> 01:16:07,097
Another little gift
from the enchantress.

1268
01:16:10,649 --> 01:16:13,607
A book that truly allows you
to escape.

1269
01:16:13,819 --> 01:16:15,435
(BLOWS)

1270
01:16:19,825 --> 01:16:20,860
How amazing!

1271
01:16:21,911 --> 01:16:24,494
It was her cruelest trick of all.

1272
01:16:25,081 --> 01:16:27,243
It was just another curse.

1273
01:16:27,333 --> 01:16:31,452
The outside world has no place
for a creature like me...

1274
01:16:32,004 --> 01:16:33,995
but it can for you.

1275
01:16:39,762 --> 01:16:43,175
Think of the one place
you've always wanted to see.

1276
01:16:45,851 --> 01:16:49,469
Now find it in your mind's eye.

1277
01:16:50,064 --> 01:16:51,850
Then feel it in your heart.

1278
01:17:22,304 --> 01:17:24,261
Where did you take us?

1279
01:17:24,807 --> 01:17:26,013
Paris.

1280
01:17:26,684 --> 01:17:28,846
Oh, I love Paris.

1281
01:17:30,437 --> 01:17:32,348
What would you like to see first?

1282
01:17:32,523 --> 01:17:33,684
Notre Dame...

1283
01:17:33,816 --> 01:17:35,682
The Champs-Élysées...

1284
01:17:35,860 --> 01:17:36,860
No?

1285
01:17:36,986 --> 01:17:38,977
Too touristy?

1286
01:17:39,905 --> 01:17:42,897
It's so much smaller
than I imagined.

1287
01:17:52,376 --> 01:17:56,085
(SINGING)
♪ <i>This is the Paris of my childhood</i> ♪

1288
01:17:57,256 --> 01:18:01,295
♪ <i>These were ♪
♪ the borders of my life</i> ♪

1289
01:18:01,468 --> 01:18:05,883
♪ <i>In this crumbling, dusty attic</i> ♪

1290
01:18:06,056 --> 01:18:10,050
♪ <i>Where an artist loved his wife</i> ♪

1291
01:18:11,061 --> 01:18:15,396
♪ <i>Easy to remember</i> ♪

1292
01:18:15,524 --> 01:18:19,313
♪ <i>Harder to move on</i> ♪

1293
01:18:22,281 --> 01:18:25,649
♪ <i>Knowing the Paris of my childhood</i> ♪

1294
01:18:27,328 --> 01:18:29,569
♪ <i>Is gone</i> ♪

1295
01:18:37,004 --> 01:18:38,494
What happened to your mother?

1296
01:18:38,589 --> 01:18:41,957
It was the one story
Papa could never bring himself to tell.

1297
01:18:42,092 --> 01:18:43,799
I knew better than to ask.

1298
01:18:44,511 --> 01:18:48,300
Oh. A doctor's mask.

1299
01:18:56,607 --> 01:18:58,018
Plague.

1300
01:18:58,108 --> 01:18:59,269
(BABY CRYING)

1301
01:19:00,694 --> 01:19:02,435
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

1302
01:19:03,614 --> 01:19:05,605
You must leave now.

1303
01:19:06,450 --> 01:19:08,782
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

1304
01:19:09,536 --> 01:19:10,576
BELLE'S MOTHER: <i>Quickly...</i>

1305
01:19:10,663 --> 01:19:12,370
before it takes her too.

1306
01:19:18,504 --> 01:19:20,711
(BABY BELLE CRYING)

1307
01:19:30,474 --> 01:19:33,466
I'm sorry I ever
called your father a thief.

1308
01:19:36,146 --> 01:19:37,682
(WHISPERS) Let's go home.

1309
01:19:44,154 --> 01:19:45,986
LEFOU:
This is some storm, huh?

1310
01:19:46,156 --> 01:19:48,397
At least
we're not tied to a tree

1311
01:19:48,492 --> 01:19:49,982
in the middle of nowhere...

1312
01:19:50,077 --> 01:19:52,068
surrounded by bloodthirsty wolves.

1313
01:19:52,246 --> 01:19:54,032
You know it's not too late.

1314
01:19:54,164 --> 01:19:55,404
We could always turn back...

1315
01:19:57,710 --> 01:19:58,710
It's just...

1316
01:19:58,877 --> 01:20:01,335
every time I close my eyes...

1317
01:20:01,463 --> 01:20:03,170
I picture Maurice stranded alone.

1318
01:20:03,257 --> 01:20:04,497
And then when I open them...

1319
01:20:05,050 --> 01:20:06,336
he's...

1320
01:20:07,678 --> 01:20:09,589
Maurice!

1321
01:20:09,847 --> 01:20:11,679
(THUNDER RUMBLES)

1322
01:20:11,765 --> 01:20:13,176
Gaston...

1323
01:20:13,350 --> 01:20:15,682
did you try to kill Maurice?

1324
01:20:15,936 --> 01:20:17,677
(ALL MURMURING)

1325
01:20:19,023 --> 01:20:20,684
Maurice!

1326
01:20:20,858 --> 01:20:22,098
Thank heavens!

1327
01:20:22,693 --> 01:20:24,934
I've spent the last five days...

1328
01:20:25,029 --> 01:20:27,020
- trying to find you.
- You tried to kill me.

1329
01:20:27,114 --> 01:20:28,855
You left me to the wolves.

1330
01:20:29,033 --> 01:20:30,194
GASTON: Wolves?

1331
01:20:30,367 --> 01:20:33,109
It's one thing to rave
about your delusions.

1332
01:20:33,203 --> 01:20:35,535
It's another to accuse me
of attempted murder.

1333
01:20:35,622 --> 01:20:36,828
JEAN: Maurice...

1334
01:20:37,541 --> 01:20:40,078
do you have any proof
of what you're saying?

1335
01:20:42,379 --> 01:20:44,711
Ask Agathe. She rescued me.

1336
01:20:44,840 --> 01:20:46,251
GASTON: (LAUGHING) Agathe!

1337
01:20:47,885 --> 01:20:50,217
You'd hang your accusations
on the testimony...

1338
01:20:50,346 --> 01:20:51,711
of a filthy hag?

1339
01:20:51,889 --> 01:20:53,926
No offense, Agathe.

1340
01:20:56,477 --> 01:20:57,933
<i>Monsieur</i> LeFou.

1341
01:20:58,520 --> 01:21:01,057
He was there. He saw it all.

1342
01:21:01,815 --> 01:21:02,815
Me?

1343
01:21:02,900 --> 01:21:04,436
You're right.

1344
01:21:04,610 --> 01:21:06,396
Don't take my word for it.

1345
01:21:06,570 --> 01:21:07,731
LeFou...

1346
01:21:09,239 --> 01:21:11,196
my dearest companion...

1347
01:21:11,283 --> 01:21:12,318
did I...

1348
01:21:12,493 --> 01:21:15,861
your oldest friend
and most loyal compatriot...

1349
01:21:15,954 --> 01:21:19,572
try to kill the father
of the only woman I've ever loved?

1350
01:21:19,750 --> 01:21:23,163
Well, it's a complicated question
on a number of accounts...

1351
01:21:23,587 --> 01:21:24,587
(GASPS)

1352
01:21:24,838 --> 01:21:26,545
But no.

1353
01:21:27,800 --> 01:21:30,007
- No, he did not.
- (PEOPLE MURMURING)

1354
01:21:30,260 --> 01:21:31,260
You...

1355
01:21:32,679 --> 01:21:33,679
- (GRUNTS)
- (PEOPLE GASP)

1356
01:21:34,890 --> 01:21:35,925
(MAURICE GROANS)

1357
01:21:38,477 --> 01:21:39,842
Maurice...

1358
01:21:40,813 --> 01:21:42,269
it pains me to say this,

1359
01:21:42,356 --> 01:21:45,064
but you've become a danger
to yourself and others.

1360
01:21:45,150 --> 01:21:48,233
No wonder Belle ran away.

1361
01:21:48,320 --> 01:21:49,776
You need help, sir.

1362
01:21:49,947 --> 01:21:52,530
A place to heal
your troubled mind.

1363
01:21:55,452 --> 01:21:57,568
Everything's going to be fine.

1364
01:21:57,663 --> 01:21:58,994
Just fine.

1365
01:22:02,918 --> 01:22:04,229
THE BEAST: Well, I saw her
in the ballroom...

1366
01:22:04,253 --> 01:22:06,189
and said, "You're making
everything look so beautiful."

1367
01:22:06,213 --> 01:22:07,624
"We should have
a dance tonight."

1368
01:22:07,714 --> 01:22:09,955
I never imagined
she'd actually say yes.

1369
01:22:10,134 --> 01:22:11,249
What was I thinking?

1370
01:22:11,385 --> 01:22:13,797
LUMIÈRE: No, Master.
It's perfect.

1371
01:22:13,971 --> 01:22:16,633
The rose has only four petals left
which means tonight...

1372
01:22:16,765 --> 01:22:18,802
you can tell her how you feel.

1373
01:22:19,393 --> 01:22:20,804
I feel like a fool.

1374
01:22:21,728 --> 01:22:23,639
She will never love me.

1375
01:22:23,772 --> 01:22:24,807
Do not be discouraged.

1376
01:22:25,065 --> 01:22:26,146
(SPITS)

1377
01:22:26,275 --> 01:22:27,640
She is the one.

1378
01:22:27,818 --> 01:22:30,105
I wish you'd stop saying that!

1379
01:22:30,320 --> 01:22:31,481
(SIGHS)

1380
01:22:31,572 --> 01:22:32,983
There is no "one."

1381
01:22:33,157 --> 01:22:34,739
You care for her, don't you?

1382
01:22:34,825 --> 01:22:37,658
Well, then,
woo her with beautiful music

1383
01:22:37,744 --> 01:22:39,075
and romantic candlelight.

1384
01:22:39,246 --> 01:22:42,364
Yes, and when
the moment's just right...

1385
01:22:42,499 --> 01:22:44,206
- (GIGGLES)
- Well, how will I know?

1386
01:22:44,376 --> 01:22:45,866
You will feel slightly nauseous.

1387
01:22:46,044 --> 01:22:48,411
Don't worry, Master.
You'll do fine.

1388
01:22:48,589 --> 01:22:50,751
MRS. POTTS:
Just stop being so nervous

1389
01:22:50,841 --> 01:22:53,128
and tell Belle how you feel.

1390
01:22:53,218 --> 01:22:54,218
Because if you don't...

1391
01:22:54,303 --> 01:22:57,546
I promise you'll be drinking cold tea
for the rest of your days!

1392
01:22:57,681 --> 01:22:59,297
- In the dark.
- Covered in dust.

1393
01:22:59,391 --> 01:23:02,179
- Dark and very, very dusty.
- (DINGS)

1394
01:23:02,769 --> 01:23:04,100
Start with the hair.

1395
01:23:04,188 --> 01:23:05,974
Women love nice hair!

1396
01:23:06,064 --> 01:23:07,429
I'll take
the fingers and toes.

1397
01:23:07,524 --> 01:23:10,562
Chapeau, brush those teeth.
They need it.

1398
01:23:10,694 --> 01:23:11,934
LUMIÈRE: Dip, dip.

1399
01:23:12,029 --> 01:23:14,066
Snip, snip.

1400
01:23:14,865 --> 01:23:16,526
Polish the nails.

1401
01:23:16,617 --> 01:23:18,528
Shine the horns.

1402
01:23:18,660 --> 01:23:20,025
PLUMETTE:
Eyes closed. Poof, poof.

1403
01:23:20,120 --> 01:23:21,781
LUMIÈRE:
And to top it all off...

1404
01:23:23,332 --> 01:23:24,663
Voilà!

1405
01:23:26,043 --> 01:23:28,705
Okay, I can fix this.

1406
01:23:29,171 --> 01:23:30,286
(SIGHS)

1407
01:23:37,179 --> 01:23:39,762
Oh! Beautiful!

1408
01:23:39,932 --> 01:23:41,343
But something is missing.

1409
01:23:42,226 --> 01:23:44,388
Oh, yes.

1410
01:23:45,187 --> 01:23:48,396
The finishing touch.

1411
01:24:53,297 --> 01:24:57,256
MRS. POTTS: (SINGING)
♪ <i>Tale as old as time</i> ♪

1412
01:24:58,635 --> 01:25:02,469
♪ <i>True as it can be</i> ♪

1413
01:25:04,308 --> 01:25:06,970
♪ <i>Barely even friends</i> ♪

1414
01:25:07,144 --> 01:25:11,934
♪ <i>Then somebody ♪
♪ bends unexpectedly</i> ♪

1415
01:25:15,110 --> 01:25:17,977
♪ <i>Just a little change</i> ♪

1416
01:25:20,324 --> 01:25:22,691
♪ <i>Small to say the least</i> ♪

1417
01:25:23,285 --> 01:25:26,118
♪ <i>Both a little scared</i> ♪

1418
01:25:26,204 --> 01:25:28,161
♪ <i>Neither one prepared</i> ♪

1419
01:25:29,166 --> 01:25:33,535
♪ <i>Beauty and the Beast</i> ♪

1420
01:25:44,348 --> 01:25:47,261
♪ <i>Everjust the same</i> ♪

1421
01:25:50,854 --> 01:25:55,143
♪ <i>Ever a surprise</i> ♪

1422
01:25:57,861 --> 01:26:00,478
♪ <i>Ever as before</i> ♪

1423
01:26:00,656 --> 01:26:03,739
♪ <i>Everjust as sure</i> ♪

1424
01:26:03,909 --> 01:26:08,995
♪ <i>As the sun will rise</i> ♪

1425
01:26:10,916 --> 01:26:14,580
♪ <i>Tale as old as time</i> ♪

1426
01:26:17,255 --> 01:26:21,419
♪ <i>Tune as old as song</i> ♪

1427
01:26:23,720 --> 01:26:26,052
♪ <i>Bittersweet and strange</i> ♪

1428
01:26:26,223 --> 01:26:29,341
♪ <i>Finding you can change</i> ♪

1429
01:26:29,434 --> 01:26:32,927
♪ <i>Learning you were wrong</i> ♪

1430
01:26:45,701 --> 01:26:49,319
♪ <i>Certain as the sun</i> ♪

1431
01:26:52,207 --> 01:26:55,074
♪ <i>Rising in the east</i> ♪

1432
01:26:55,252 --> 01:26:58,085
♪ <i>Tale as old as time</i> ♪

1433
01:26:58,255 --> 01:27:01,589
♪ <i>Song as old as rhyme</i> ♪

1434
01:27:01,758 --> 01:27:06,173
♪ <i>Beauty and the Beast</i> ♪

1435
01:27:08,223 --> 01:27:11,557
♪ <i>Tale as old as time</i> ♪

1436
01:27:11,727 --> 01:27:14,936
♪ <i>Song as old as rhyme</i> ♪

1437
01:27:16,273 --> 01:27:22,315
♪ <i>Beauty and the Beast</i> ♪

1438
01:27:38,795 --> 01:27:41,537
(SIGHS)
♪ I haven't danced in years. ♪

1439
01:27:42,632 --> 01:27:44,794
I'd almost forgotten the feeling.

1440
01:27:45,135 --> 01:27:46,796
(EXHALES)

1441
01:27:54,644 --> 01:27:56,885
It's foolish, I suppose...

1442
01:27:57,814 --> 01:28:00,522
for a creature like me to hope...

1443
01:28:00,692 --> 01:28:03,605
that one day he might earn
your affection.

1444
01:28:04,654 --> 01:28:06,565
I don't know.

1445
01:28:06,656 --> 01:28:07,987
Really?

1446
01:28:09,159 --> 01:28:11,275
You think
you could be happy here?

1447
01:28:16,416 --> 01:28:19,283
Can anybody be happy
if they aren't free?

1448
01:28:29,304 --> 01:28:30,886
My father taught me to dance.

1449
01:28:32,682 --> 01:28:34,343
I used to step on his toes a lot.

1450
01:28:37,854 --> 01:28:39,936
You must miss him.

1451
01:28:42,359 --> 01:28:43,565
Very much.

1452
01:28:50,492 --> 01:28:52,483
Would you like to see him?

1453
01:29:01,378 --> 01:29:03,164
I'd like to see my father.

1454
01:29:04,589 --> 01:29:06,250
(INAUDIBLE)

1455
01:29:06,550 --> 01:29:07,915
Papa!

1456
01:29:09,344 --> 01:29:11,335
What are they doing to him?

1457
01:29:11,471 --> 01:29:13,132
He's in trouble!

1458
01:29:14,474 --> 01:29:15,839
Then you must go to him.

1459
01:29:18,478 --> 01:29:19,593
What did you say?

1460
01:29:20,814 --> 01:29:22,896
You must go to him.

1461
01:29:24,734 --> 01:29:26,145
No time to waste.

1462
01:29:27,279 --> 01:29:28,769
(GASPS SOFTLY)

1463
01:29:31,449 --> 01:29:32,484
No...

1464
01:29:32,617 --> 01:29:34,199
you keep it with you.

1465
01:29:36,288 --> 01:29:39,246
Then you'll always have a way
to look back on me.

1466
01:29:44,629 --> 01:29:45,994
Thank you.

1467
01:30:02,772 --> 01:30:04,137
(EXHALES)

1468
01:30:23,001 --> 01:30:24,491
Oh...

1469
01:30:25,545 --> 01:30:26,580
(SIGHS)

1470
01:30:31,509 --> 01:30:33,045
Well, Master,
I have had my doubts,

1471
01:30:33,136 --> 01:30:34,696
but everything
is moving like clockwork.

1472
01:30:34,971 --> 01:30:37,383
True love really does win the day!

1473
01:30:40,310 --> 01:30:41,846
I let her go.

1474
01:30:41,978 --> 01:30:43,594
You what?

1475
01:30:43,772 --> 01:30:45,763
Master, how could you do that?

1476
01:30:45,857 --> 01:30:47,598
I had to.

1477
01:30:48,443 --> 01:30:49,274
But why?

1478
01:30:49,361 --> 01:30:51,398
Because he loves her.

1479
01:30:52,072 --> 01:30:53,437
Then why are we not human?

1480
01:30:53,531 --> 01:30:57,069
Because she doesn't love him.
And now, it's too late.

1481
01:30:57,243 --> 01:30:59,280
But she might still come back.

1482
01:30:59,371 --> 01:31:00,486
No.

1483
01:31:01,331 --> 01:31:02,742
I set her free.

1484
01:31:04,250 --> 01:31:07,333
I'm sorry I couldn't do
the same for all of you.

1485
01:31:07,462 --> 01:31:09,123
Now, go.

1486
01:31:09,214 --> 01:31:11,455
Our time is almost past.

1487
01:31:15,887 --> 01:31:17,252
- Come, my love.
- (SIGHS)

1488
01:31:20,183 --> 01:31:23,096
(SINGING)
♪ <i>I was the one who had it all</i> ♪

1489
01:31:25,021 --> 01:31:28,013
♪ <i>I was the master of my fate</i> ♪

1490
01:31:29,693 --> 01:31:34,358
♪ <i>I never needed anybody in my life</i> ♪

1491
01:31:34,531 --> 01:31:38,115
♪ <i>I learned the truth too late</i> ♪

1492
01:31:39,202 --> 01:31:42,445
♪ <i>I'll never shake away the pain</i> ♪

1493
01:31:43,790 --> 01:31:47,408
♪ <i>I close my eyes ♪
♪ but she's still there</i> ♪

1494
01:31:48,545 --> 01:31:52,880
♪ <i>I let her steal ♪
♪ into my melancholy heart</i> ♪

1495
01:31:53,550 --> 01:31:56,713
♪ <i>It's more than I can bear</i> ♪

1496
01:31:59,723 --> 01:32:05,059
♪ <i>Now I know ♪
♪ she'll never leave me</i> ♪

1497
01:32:05,228 --> 01:32:09,643
♪ <i>Even as she runs away</i> ♪

1498
01:32:09,816 --> 01:32:14,401
♪ <i>She will still torment me ♪
♪ Calm me, hurt me</i> ♪

1499
01:32:14,571 --> 01:32:17,814
♪ <i>Move me, come what may</i> ♪

1500
01:32:19,784 --> 01:32:23,743
♪ <i>Wasting in my lonely tower</i> ♪

1501
01:32:23,830 --> 01:32:27,664
♪ <i>Waiting by an open door</i> ♪

1502
01:32:29,002 --> 01:32:32,211
♪ <i>I'll fool myself ♪
♪ she'll walk right in</i> ♪

1503
01:32:34,007 --> 01:32:38,046
♪ <i>And be with me for evermore</i> ♪

1504
01:32:41,014 --> 01:32:44,223
♪ <i>I rage against the trials of love</i> ♪

1505
01:32:45,435 --> 01:32:48,427
♪ <i>I curse the fading of the light</i> ♪

1506
01:32:50,106 --> 01:32:53,849
♪ <i>Though she's already flown ♪
♪ So far beyond my reach</i> ♪

1507
01:32:54,486 --> 01:33:00,573
♪ <i>She's never out of sight</i> ♪

1508
01:33:00,742 --> 01:33:05,111
♪ <i>Now I know ♪
♪ she'll never leave me</i> ♪

1509
01:33:06,039 --> 01:33:10,875
♪ <i>Even as she fades from view</i> ♪

1510
01:33:10,960 --> 01:33:12,792
♪ <i>She will still inspire me</i> ♪

1511
01:33:12,962 --> 01:33:18,583
♪ <i>Be a part of everything I do</i> ♪

1512
01:33:19,469 --> 01:33:23,554
♪ <i>Wasting in my lonely tower</i> ♪

1513
01:33:24,182 --> 01:33:27,641
♪ <i>Waiting by an open door</i> ♪

1514
01:33:29,020 --> 01:33:32,388
♪ <i>I'll fool myself ♪
♪ she'll walk right in</i> ♪

1515
01:33:33,483 --> 01:33:36,521
♪ <i>And as the long, long nights begin</i> ♪

1516
01:33:38,029 --> 01:33:41,067
♪ <i>I'll think of all that might have been</i> ♪

1517
01:33:41,908 --> 01:33:48,951
♪ <i>Waiting here for evermore</i> ♪

1518
01:34:09,435 --> 01:34:10,470
This man is weak.

1519
01:34:10,562 --> 01:34:11,562
Please!

1520
01:34:12,063 --> 01:34:13,645
He needs a hospital...

1521
01:34:13,731 --> 01:34:14,937
not an asylum!

1522
01:34:15,316 --> 01:34:16,316
(GRUNTS)

1523
01:34:18,486 --> 01:34:21,353
Have you ever seen the inside
of a mad house, Maurice?

1524
01:34:21,531 --> 01:34:23,442
You wouldn't last a week.

1525
01:34:23,533 --> 01:34:25,678
Just give me your daughter's hand,
and I'll set you free.

1526
01:34:25,702 --> 01:34:26,942
Never.

1527
01:34:30,039 --> 01:34:31,575
Take him away!

1528
01:34:31,791 --> 01:34:32,872
(HORSE WHINNYING)

1529
01:34:39,883 --> 01:34:40,883
Stop!

1530
01:34:53,563 --> 01:34:54,563
Papa.

1531
01:34:54,731 --> 01:34:56,411
MAURICE: Oh, Belle.
I thought I'd lost you.

1532
01:34:56,441 --> 01:34:58,648
Let him out! He's hurt.

1533
01:34:58,735 --> 01:34:59,975
We can't do that, miss.

1534
01:35:00,069 --> 01:35:01,509
But we'll take
very good care of him.

1535
01:35:01,654 --> 01:35:03,565
My father's not crazy.

1536
01:35:03,740 --> 01:35:05,356
Gaston, tell him!

1537
01:35:05,450 --> 01:35:07,236
You know how loyal I am
to your family...

1538
01:35:07,410 --> 01:35:10,118
but your father's been making
some unbelievable claims.

1539
01:35:10,288 --> 01:35:11,904
It's true, Belle.

1540
01:35:12,081 --> 01:35:14,493
He's been raving about a beast...

1541
01:35:14,584 --> 01:35:15,584
in a castle!

1542
01:35:15,627 --> 01:35:18,415
I've just come from the castle
and there is a beast!

1543
01:35:18,546 --> 01:35:21,629
You'd say anything to set him free.
Your word is hardly proof.

1544
01:35:21,758 --> 01:35:23,294
You want proof?

1545
01:35:25,261 --> 01:35:26,968
Show me the Beast!

1546
01:35:29,849 --> 01:35:31,590
(ALL GASPING)

1547
01:35:35,271 --> 01:35:36,682
(ALL MURMURING)

1548
01:35:36,773 --> 01:35:38,229
There's your proof.

1549
01:35:39,734 --> 01:35:40,849
This is sorcery!

1550
01:35:43,279 --> 01:35:45,816
Look at this beast!

1551
01:35:45,949 --> 01:35:47,349
- Look at his fangs!
- (ALL EXCLAIM)

1552
01:35:48,368 --> 01:35:49,608
His claws!

1553
01:35:49,702 --> 01:35:52,034
No. Don't be afraid.

1554
01:35:52,205 --> 01:35:54,446
He's gentle and kind.

1555
01:35:54,540 --> 01:35:56,281
(ALL MURMURING)

1556
01:35:56,501 --> 01:35:59,289
The monster has her under his spell.

1557
01:35:59,462 --> 01:36:00,748
If I didn't know better,

1558
01:36:00,838 --> 01:36:03,330
I'd say she even cared for him!

1559
01:36:03,633 --> 01:36:05,544
He's not a monster, Gaston.

1560
01:36:05,718 --> 01:36:06,833
You are!

1561
01:36:08,805 --> 01:36:10,170
The Beast wouldn't hurt anyone.

1562
01:36:10,348 --> 01:36:12,134
I've heard of the effects
of dark magic...

1563
01:36:12,267 --> 01:36:15,134
but I've never before seen it
with my own eyes!

1564
01:36:15,311 --> 01:36:16,472
This is a threat

1565
01:36:16,604 --> 01:36:18,604
- to our very existence!
- (ALL AGREEING IN UNISON)

1566
01:36:19,524 --> 01:36:21,731
We can't have her
running off to warn the beast.

1567
01:36:21,818 --> 01:36:22,979
Lock her up too.

1568
01:36:23,111 --> 01:36:24,601
- No!
- TOM: Come here!

1569
01:36:24,696 --> 01:36:26,232
- (GRUNTS)
- Shut up!

1570
01:36:26,322 --> 01:36:27,967
BELLE: You won't get away
with this, Gaston!

1571
01:36:27,991 --> 01:36:30,198
- MAURICE: Oh, Belle!
- (PEOPLE MURMURING)

1572
01:36:30,952 --> 01:36:32,863
Gaston,
with all due respect...

1573
01:36:32,996 --> 01:36:34,657
Do you want to be next?

1574
01:36:35,790 --> 01:36:37,030
Fetch my horse.

1575
01:36:37,166 --> 01:36:38,452
Stand guard!

1576
01:36:38,543 --> 01:36:39,704
Don't let them escape.

1577
01:36:39,877 --> 01:36:42,335
This creature will curse us all
if we don't stop him.

1578
01:36:42,463 --> 01:36:43,578
(ALL AGREEING IN UNISON)

1579
01:36:43,965 --> 01:36:46,753
Well, I say,
we kill the beast!

1580
01:36:46,843 --> 01:36:47,924
ALL: Kill the beast!

1581
01:36:48,219 --> 01:36:50,426
(ALL AGREEING)

1582
01:36:50,680 --> 01:36:52,199
(SINGING)
♪ <i>We're not safe until he's dead</i> ♪

1583
01:36:52,223 --> 01:36:53,884
♪ <i>He'll come stalking us at night</i> ♪

1584
01:36:54,058 --> 01:36:57,176
♪ <i>Set to sacrifice our children ♪
♪ To his monstrous appetite</i> ♪

1585
01:36:57,353 --> 01:36:58,969
♪ <i>He'll wreak havoc on our village</i> ♪

1586
01:36:59,063 --> 01:37:00,519
♪ <i>If we let him wander free</i> ♪

1587
01:37:00,648 --> 01:37:04,061
♪ <i>So it's time to take some action, boys</i> ♪

1588
01:37:04,235 --> 01:37:09,651
♪ <i>It's time to follow me</i> ♪

1589
01:37:09,866 --> 01:37:11,027
(ALL SHOUTING)

1590
01:37:11,367 --> 01:37:13,887
♪ <i>Through the mist, through the wood ♪
♪ Through the darkness and the shadows</i> ♪

1591
01:37:13,911 --> 01:37:17,245
♪ <i>It's a nightmare ♪
♪ But it's one exciting ride</i> ♪

1592
01:37:17,373 --> 01:37:20,832
♪ <i>Say a prayer, then we're there ♪
♪ At the drawbridge of a castle</i> ♪

1593
01:37:21,002 --> 01:37:24,370
♪ <i>And there's something ♪
♪ truly terrible inside</i> ♪

1594
01:37:24,505 --> 01:37:27,213
♪ <i>It's a beast ♪
♪ He's got fangs, razor sharp ones</i> ♪

1595
01:37:27,383 --> 01:37:30,546
♪ <i>Massive paws, ♪
♪ killer claws for the feast</i> ♪

1596
01:37:30,678 --> 01:37:32,294
♪ <i>Hear him roar, see him foam</i> ♪

1597
01:37:32,388 --> 01:37:36,052
♪ <i>But we're not coming home ♪
♪ 'Til he's dead</i> ♪

1598
01:37:36,184 --> 01:37:37,219
♪ <i>Good and dead</i> ♪

1599
01:37:37,352 --> 01:37:38,717
ALL: ♪<i>Kill the beast!</i> ♪

1600
01:37:41,064 --> 01:37:42,725
♪ <i>Light your torch, ♪
♪ mount your horse</i> ♪

1601
01:37:42,815 --> 01:37:44,585
♪ <i>Screw your courage ♪
♪ to the sticking place</i> ♪

1602
01:37:44,609 --> 01:37:47,852
ALL: ♪<i>We're counting
on Gaston to lead the way</i> ♪

1603
01:37:47,945 --> 01:37:51,028
♪ <i>Call it war, call it threat ♪
♪ You can bet they all will follow</i> ♪

1604
01:37:51,199 --> 01:37:54,237
♪ <i>For in times like this ♪
♪ They'll do just as I say</i> ♪

1605
01:37:54,410 --> 01:37:57,619
♪ <i>There's a beast running wild ♪
♪ There's no question</i> ♪

1606
01:37:57,789 --> 01:38:00,907
♪ <i>But I fear ♪
♪ the wrong monster's released</i> ♪

1607
01:38:01,084 --> 01:38:04,577
ALL: ♪<i>Sally forth, tally ho
Grab your sword, grab your bow</i> ♪

1608
01:38:04,670 --> 01:38:08,959
♪ <i>Praise the Lord, and here we go</i> ♪

1609
01:38:12,220 --> 01:38:13,927
Show me the castle.

1610
01:38:16,474 --> 01:38:18,090
At least he has finally
learned to love.

1611
01:38:18,267 --> 01:38:21,225
A lot of good that does us
if she doesn't love him in return.

1612
01:38:21,396 --> 01:38:25,685
No. This is the first time
I've had any real hope she would.

1613
01:38:25,858 --> 01:38:27,669
- (HORSE WHINNYING IN DISTANCE)
- Did you hear that, Mama?

1614
01:38:27,693 --> 01:38:29,149
Is it her? Is she coming back?

1615
01:38:29,278 --> 01:38:30,439
LUMIÈRE: Could it be?

1616
01:38:30,613 --> 01:38:32,103
PLUMETTE: (GASPS) I told you!

1617
01:38:32,281 --> 01:38:33,487
<i>Sacré bleu!</i>

1618
01:38:33,616 --> 01:38:34,902
Invaders!

1619
01:38:34,992 --> 01:38:36,232
MRS. POTTS: Ruffians!

1620
01:38:36,411 --> 01:38:38,243
Well, there you go.

1621
01:38:38,413 --> 01:38:40,495
So much for true love.

1622
01:38:40,623 --> 01:38:42,284
Man the barricades...

1623
01:38:42,458 --> 01:38:45,291
and hold fast!

1624
01:38:45,378 --> 01:38:46,618
Move aside!

1625
01:38:46,754 --> 01:38:49,837
♪ (SINGING) <i>Hearts ablaze, banners high ♪
♪ We go marching into battle</i> ♪

1626
01:38:49,966 --> 01:38:52,799
♪ <i>Unafraid, although ♪
♪ the danger's just increased</i> ♪

1627
01:38:54,762 --> 01:38:57,800
MOB: ♪<i>Raise the flag, sing the song
Here we come, we're fifty strong</i> ♪

1628
01:38:57,974 --> 01:39:00,966
♪ <i>And fifty Frenchmen can't be wrong</i> ♪

1629
01:39:01,102 --> 01:39:02,308
♪ <i>Let's kill the beast!</i> ♪

1630
01:39:03,104 --> 01:39:04,765
(GRUNTING)

1631
01:39:05,898 --> 01:39:07,184
COGSWORTH: We need help.

1632
01:39:10,778 --> 01:39:13,065
- I have to warn the Beast.
- Warn him?

1633
01:39:13,239 --> 01:39:15,150
How did you get away from him?

1634
01:39:16,492 --> 01:39:18,483
He let me go, Papa.

1635
01:39:19,120 --> 01:39:20,781
He sent me back to you.

1636
01:39:21,038 --> 01:39:22,870
(STAMMERS) I don't understand.

1637
01:39:29,005 --> 01:39:30,461
Where did you...

1638
01:39:30,631 --> 01:39:32,998
He took me there.

1639
01:39:36,262 --> 01:39:38,799
I know what happened to <i>Maman.</i>

1640
01:39:39,098 --> 01:39:41,590
Then you know
why I had to leave her there.

1641
01:39:41,684 --> 01:39:42,799
I had to protect you.

1642
01:39:43,144 --> 01:39:46,102
I've always tried to protect
my little girl.

1643
01:39:46,189 --> 01:39:47,600
Probably too much.

1644
01:39:48,399 --> 01:39:50,310
I understand.

1645
01:39:54,071 --> 01:39:55,311
(KISSES)

1646
01:39:58,034 --> 01:39:59,490
Will you help me now?

1647
01:39:59,619 --> 01:40:01,530
It's dangerous.

1648
01:40:01,662 --> 01:40:02,823
Yes.

1649
01:40:03,372 --> 01:40:04,703
Yes, it is.

1650
01:40:08,211 --> 01:40:10,122
I could try to pick the lock.

1651
01:40:10,796 --> 01:40:11,911
After all...

1652
01:40:12,048 --> 01:40:15,962
it's only gears and springs.

1653
01:40:18,554 --> 01:40:20,420
But I would need...

1654
01:40:20,556 --> 01:40:23,093
something long and sharp.

1655
01:40:24,310 --> 01:40:25,391
Like that.

1656
01:40:25,561 --> 01:40:27,017
Perfect.

1657
01:40:28,231 --> 01:40:30,097
(PEOPLE SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

1658
01:40:31,400 --> 01:40:32,890
(PANTING)
Oh, excuse me, Master.

1659
01:40:33,069 --> 01:40:34,776
(STAMMERS)
I'm so sorry to disturb you.

1660
01:40:34,946 --> 01:40:36,482
She's not coming back.

1661
01:40:37,490 --> 01:40:38,605
No.

1662
01:40:38,783 --> 01:40:40,740
They're breaking down the doors!

1663
01:40:41,536 --> 01:40:43,493
Doesn't matter now.

1664
01:40:43,579 --> 01:40:46,162
Just let them come.

1665
01:40:46,249 --> 01:40:48,957
MOB: (SINGING) ♪<i>Kill the beast!
Kill the beast!</i> ♪

1666
01:40:49,085 --> 01:40:50,371
This isn't working!

1667
01:40:50,545 --> 01:40:51,660
I know what to do.

1668
01:40:51,796 --> 01:40:54,083
MOB: ♪<i>Kill the beast!
Kill the beast!</i> ♪

1669
01:40:54,423 --> 01:40:56,209
♪ <i>Kill the beast!</i> ♪

1670
01:40:57,343 --> 01:40:58,925
(PEOPLE GROANING)

1671
01:41:03,808 --> 01:41:05,970
Are you not
the least bit concerned...

1672
01:41:06,102 --> 01:41:07,934
that this castle might be haunted?

1673
01:41:09,397 --> 01:41:11,764
Don't lose your nerve, LeFou.

1674
01:41:11,983 --> 01:41:13,098
MAN: Where are we?

1675
01:41:14,777 --> 01:41:18,816
This place seems familiar.

1676
01:41:18,990 --> 01:41:20,981
Like I've been here before.

1677
01:41:23,828 --> 01:41:25,114
Oh, hello, there.

1678
01:41:25,788 --> 01:41:28,576
You must be the talking tea cup.

1679
01:41:29,333 --> 01:41:30,368
And you must be...

1680
01:41:30,459 --> 01:41:31,699
his grandmother.

1681
01:41:31,836 --> 01:41:33,668
(GASPS) Grandmother?

1682
01:41:33,838 --> 01:41:35,954
- Attack!
- (GASPS)

1683
01:41:36,716 --> 01:41:38,332
Oh, hello! (LAUGHS)

1684
01:41:38,676 --> 01:41:39,962
(PEOPLE SHOUTING)

1685
01:41:40,845 --> 01:41:42,051
(MEN GROANING)

1686
01:41:46,767 --> 01:41:48,474
- (DINGING)
- (GROANING)

1687
01:41:52,815 --> 01:41:54,055
Gaston! (SCREAMS)

1688
01:41:54,483 --> 01:41:55,848
(GROANS)

1689
01:41:57,903 --> 01:41:59,109
Gaston.

1690
01:41:59,238 --> 01:42:00,319
Help.

1691
01:42:00,489 --> 01:42:01,820
Sorry, old friend.

1692
01:42:02,450 --> 01:42:04,191
It's hero time.

1693
01:42:04,535 --> 01:42:05,696
Ooh, ouch!

1694
01:42:07,455 --> 01:42:08,455
(EXHALES)

1695
01:42:24,180 --> 01:42:25,295
Hello.

1696
01:42:25,973 --> 01:42:28,681
Oh, uh...
I believe this is yours.

1697
01:42:28,851 --> 01:42:29,851
(PHILIPPE WHINNYING)

1698
01:42:35,232 --> 01:42:36,232
She's very headstrong.

1699
01:42:38,194 --> 01:42:39,400
Do you have children?

1700
01:42:40,821 --> 01:42:42,903
- (ALL SHOUTING)
- (GASPS)

1701
01:42:42,990 --> 01:42:46,028
PLUMETTE: No one
to protect you now, huh?

1702
01:42:46,118 --> 01:42:47,279
(PLUMETTE GIGGLING)

1703
01:42:55,086 --> 01:42:57,373
CHIP: One, two, three, four...

1704
01:42:57,463 --> 01:42:59,704
- five, six, seven, eight...
- (GROANING)

1705
01:42:59,799 --> 01:43:00,914
Good show, Chip, my boy.

1706
01:43:01,884 --> 01:43:03,545
(LAUGHS) Excellent!

1707
01:43:03,678 --> 01:43:05,760
- The infantry's arrived.
- (EXCLAIMS)

1708
01:43:06,305 --> 01:43:08,421
Now, go and teach them a lesson. Go.

1709
01:43:09,558 --> 01:43:13,347
Yes, those are called books,
you third rate musketeers.

1710
01:43:15,898 --> 01:43:17,388
Oh! I'm off.

1711
01:43:18,442 --> 01:43:19,557
(SCREAMS)

1712
01:43:23,823 --> 01:43:25,905
(CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY)
Just a clock.

1713
01:43:26,158 --> 01:43:28,274
(LAUGHS) Come here...

1714
01:43:28,452 --> 01:43:29,783
little boys.

1715
01:43:30,329 --> 01:43:32,286
I spin you this way.
I put it on.

1716
01:43:32,456 --> 01:43:36,541
- Yes, pretty little boys. Yes!
- (SCREAMING)

1717
01:43:37,503 --> 01:43:39,119
Beautiful!

1718
01:43:39,296 --> 01:43:41,287
Go, be free!

1719
01:43:41,424 --> 01:43:42,789
Be free. Be free!

1720
01:43:51,642 --> 01:43:53,258
(ALL SHOUTING)

1721
01:43:53,686 --> 01:43:55,552
(EXCLAIMS)

1722
01:43:55,813 --> 01:43:57,349
How do you like your tea?

1723
01:43:57,440 --> 01:43:58,930
- Piping hot?
- (ALL SCREAMING)

1724
01:43:59,108 --> 01:44:00,974
Or boiling?

1725
01:44:01,360 --> 01:44:02,475
Oh!

1726
01:44:02,778 --> 01:44:04,234
Mr. Potts!

1727
01:44:05,281 --> 01:44:06,897
(SCREAMING)

1728
01:44:07,450 --> 01:44:08,450
Mama!

1729
01:44:10,786 --> 01:44:12,242
Thank you!

1730
01:44:12,580 --> 01:44:13,820
(BOTH GRUNT)

1731
01:44:14,749 --> 01:44:16,469
- (BLOWS RASPBERRY)
- MRS. POTTS: Take that!

1732
01:44:17,293 --> 01:44:18,704
Nicely handled!

1733
01:44:18,794 --> 01:44:20,284
Well, I used to be
on Gaston's side...

1734
01:44:20,421 --> 01:44:22,128
but we are so
in a bad place right now.

1735
01:44:22,339 --> 01:44:24,626
- You're too good for him, anyway.
- Yeah.

1736
01:44:24,800 --> 01:44:26,040
Should we get back to it, then?

1737
01:44:27,470 --> 01:44:29,461
(MEN GRUNTING)

1738
01:44:29,805 --> 01:44:31,241
